column6: Timberland PRO Men's Pitboss 6\ Steel-Toe Boot"
column13: Quality has gone WAY downhill in the last few years
column14:
I have been wearing this style for years, but the quality has really gone downhill in the last few years. 2 pairs ago, they lasted until the soles wore down after several years - perfect. 1 pair ago, the soles fell apart within a few months - the top and bottom of the sole seem to be stiffer material, but there's empty space in between, with just a narrow band of material around the edges to fool you into thinking they're the same as the old type. The most recent pair had problems from day 1 - the hooks at the top swivel around, so the shoes come untied. I ended up needing to re-tie them repeatedly during the day. Perhaps due to this, after a few months the lace sleeve (the 3rd row from the top) popped out of the leather on one of the shoes. The right shoe also becomes very uncomfortable after a few hours and starts digging into my heel enough to cause blisters. None of this used to be a problem with this style.

Perhaps this is another example of "quality fade" and Timberland simply doesn't care (they certainly didn't seem to be motivated to do anything about the pair where the soles fell off when I called them). Maybe they're intentionally cutting corners. Regardless, this is the last Timberland product I will purchase.

column6: Skechers Performance Women's Go Walk 2 Flash Walking Shoe
column13: Very comfy but Goga mat insole is problematic with socks
column14: Very comfy and cushion-y. It's almost like not wearing shoes at all. The downside of the "Goga mat" insole is that if you're wearing socks, the rubber is so grippy that I had a really hard time getting my feet into the shoes. I sprinkled some powder in there and it helped. Over time, the Goga mat developed another annoying issue. It continually pulls my socks down inside the shoe until they're wadded up under the arch of my foot. It drives me bonkers. If they would make that insole less grippy, this would eliminate the sock issues. I know they're marketed for people who don't want to wear socks, but honestly, who exercises with no socks in a shoe that's not washable? That would equal very smelly shoe in a very short time.

column6: Merrell Men's Pulsate Mid Waterproof Hiking Boot
column13: GREAT BOOT...the Laces?  Not so much.
column14:
I purchased this boot after a long search, for my son who had foot surgery. His doctor required him to wear
something with good foot and ankle support. Normal basketball shoes don't work, as they lack arch support and
are notoriously shallow through the toe box, and narrow across the forefoot.
Merrell has been a long standing favorite with our family.
I was immediately relieved to see that this boot came in an "E Width" VERY HARD TO FIND!!!!!
It fits like a favorite slipper , with plenty of room for orthotics. Fit is true, maybe a teensy wide, but that is exactly
why we ordered the wide width.
It is a good looking boot, and doesn't look "clunky" . It is also subtle enough for schools with strict dress codes.
Hopefully one day Merrell will make an all black version of this.
My only issue with this GREAT boot, are the laces. Terrible. They are slippery, and untie themselves easily , even
when double-knotted. They are difficult to tie and keep tight. Merrell had a great boot, that won't stay tied..problem.
I don't know if "Lock Laces" will fit this boot and hold tightly enough or not, but my next "Amazon Search" will be
for laces that aren't such a pain the the neck.
Overall however, I would say this boot is a "thumbs up".

column6: West Blvd Womens Cairo Military Lace Up Combat Boots
column13: I absolutely love these combat boots
column14: I absolutely love these combat boots! They are so stylish, cute, & comfortable. I thought I had read a review that said they ran small, so I ordered an 8 & 1/2 instead of an 8 & they are very "roomy". So, I don't think I agree with the review that said they run small. If anything, I think they are true to size or a bit on the larger side. But that's not a bad thing, because it allows room for a heavier sock in the winter and/or an insole, which is what I'm using. Also, you can lace them up as tight you want, so I think the size on these is actually perfect.  I also don't agree with the review that said these boots are flimsy. They are not hard & heavy, but I think they are very sturdy & substantial--pleasantly more than I was expecting. I, too, was imagining that these boots might be rather cheaply made since they were only listed @ $17.99 when I first added them to my wish list. And I was dismayed when I saw the price had jumped up to $31.99 by the time I was ready to order. I thought I would have to be a fool to pay &31.99 for a $17.99 boot, but I really wanted the white ones & couldn't find anything else like them. So, I took a chance but wasn't honestly expecting much. So wrong! These boots are incredible & absolutely worth the &31.99! Also, they were delivered very quickly, so I am delighted with the seller as well as the product & am definitely planning on ordering another pair/color! Great purchase! Very happy!

column13: I had bought 5 pairs of the ASICS Gel Nimbus and believe these are the absolute best in cushioning and support

column6: Scarleton Soft Barrel Shoulder Bag H1485
column13: Great, but magnetic clasp leads to pieces falling off the front
column14: I love how light and soft this bag is, and how many pockets it has, but I'm not understanding the strap design on the front of the bag. See those belt looking things on either side of the bottom pocket? Well the clasp of the belt is held onto the bag by of all things a magnetic clasp fixed to the bag itself. I was bemused, but not upset when I realized this because who cares how its held on, even if there's no need to ever take this belt clasp off the purse. Then I used this bag while I was walking my dog, and when my arm brushed the bag a bit roughly, the magnetic clasp came off the bag, undid itself from the belt, and fell on the sidewalk. I'm really glad I heard it clink to the ground so I could pick it up, but now I'm worried that I'll lose these pieces when I wear the bag, so I haven't ended up using it until I can find some superglue.  Overall a great purse at a great price (as long as you're not paying the $99 original price), just with some questionable design "features".

column6: Saucony Men's Nomad TR Trail Running Shoe
column13: I really want to like these shoes
column14: When I first ordered these shoes, I was incredibly excited to get them on my feet and take them for a run into the mountains. I've run in Sauconys' before and I love their powergrid EVA. The design behind this shoe was amazing and the tread seemed to provide good traction on almost all surfaces as long as they weren't sliding underfoot(the lugs are not deep at all). The ride of the shoes was nice and provided a good combination of cushion and responsiveness. The problem with this shoe is how sloppy the fit is. I normally wear a size 9 shoe and I have a somewhat wide foot, though I comfortably run in normal width shoes. When I first put on the shoes, my toes were comfortable and everything was fitting nicely aside from the heel which is the only reason that I dislike this shoe, but it's a huge deal for me. The heel doesn't hold your foot in at all and it has too much space so yur foot can move around in it pretty easily. While running around, I never felt like I could tackle any technical because of how sloppy the heel was. If they could fix this shoe by making the heel a bit more rigid and making it more narrow, it would be an amazing shoe for trail runs of any distance.

column13: Take your time, your run will be sublime
column14: I tried on vibram shoes at a brick and mortar store, so I would know my size.  I'm getting up in years (55) and wanted to get in shape for the final leg of the journey.  The vibram website has lots of good resources on barefoot running, as does much of the web.  Follow directions and do not overdo it!  Ease into it.  Take your time.  Easy, light, smooth, fast.  It took me a number of years to do it right, but now that I have finally taken heed, I wouldn't have it any other way.  My last pair of Bikila EVOs lasted about 300 miles before the inner heel started separating from the body on both shoes.  I found a new pair on amazon at an amazing price, hit "buy now," and ran in them the day they arrived.

column13: Watch your size and you will have comfortable shoes.
column14: I have low arches and when I put these shoes on, what a relief! Many people were writing in about the size, but I chose 1 size up to alleviate the width and the compression. If you feel like these shoes are going to be too small for your feet in your regular size or if you have any foot problems, I would suggest 1 size up. The shoes stretch, but if you have bunions or pes planus (flat feet) they might be a bit snug. I bought them to wear to follow nurses around when they are doing clinicals. I must be on my feet all day. These shoes are as light as a feather and people asked me where I got them. I chose this color because the sole was lighter and it seemed to brighten up people when they saw them. The shoes have enough stretch for the swelling that feet can have at the end of the day. I am happy with this pair of shoes.

column6: Sunville - Womens Short Ankle Rubber Rain Boots
column14: I bought these to go to Ireland and when I received them I was THRILLED. They are very stylish - they look exactly like rain boots from Aldo that I waited too long to buy and couldn't find any longer, and are really cute with skinny jeans. They are also super comfortable and I could walk in them for hours. There was no chance of slipping on slippery surfaces as the rubber on the sole was awesome, and they kept my feet totally dry walking through wet grass and small puddles. The only kind of odd thing about them was the width of the opening at the ankle. I don't have super skinny ankles, but I don't have cankles either - and there was at least 2-3 inches of space around my ankles. It only really sprinkled while I was in Ireland so I didn't have much of a problem with this, but I imagine that if I was in a crazy downpour my feet would get wet just from rain falling into the shoe. Another gripe I had with them was that the inside sole kept coming out every time I pulled my foot out. I guess super glue or something would make them stick down better. Also - if you are traveling with these boots, note that they are going to be very HEAVY in your suitcase. All in all, I am very glad I bought these boots simply from how cute and stylish they are for the price and they totally worked well for me during my trip.

Too late to return!

column6: EM TRAIL N 1
column14: Oh how I love these shoes. I do a lot of hiking and have always been a boot guy. Never minded the extra weight in exchange for good support and protection. Lately, though, I've been getting into trail running, so I needed something light that could also get me through a rugged bridle trail without tearing up my feet. I first tried the Saucony Peregrine 5 but failed to find a good fit. My feet are a little wider than normal, and I found the Peregrine toe box to be too narrow. Enter Pearl Izumi. The EM N1 runs for $115, but Amazon had my size for $40 so it was a no-brainer to give them a try. They are some incredibly ugly shoes, but wow is the fit perfect for me. No heel slippage but plenty of room in the toe box for my toes to fully splay. I'd be interested to try the N2 for the extra cushioning, but I was satisfied with the support. I took them out yesterday for a 17 mile hike and had zero problems. Today my feet feel like I spent all weekend in bed. I was so impressed, I got home from my hike and immediately ordered another pair. I haven't run in them yet, but I don't foresee having any problems. If you've got a wide foot like me, do yourself a favor and try these out.

column6: Dooney & Bourke Nylon Large Pocket Satchel
column14:
Love the handbag. I bought the Clementine color so I could use it from September through November as a seasonal handbag. The Clementine color is a vibrant orange, very well made, light in weight, and a very large handbag. Perfect for traveling or at the mall to carry extras. There is one thing I do not like about the handbag, but I can live with it.
The shoulder strap is very long, as for using the bag as a crossbody handbag. The shoulder strap has two places for adjustments. The strap could use some more holes to make the strap shorter, so you can reach into the bag while it is on your shoulder. As short as I can make the shoulder strap, I will have to take the bag off of my shoulder to look for something inside.
If you look at the strap in the picture, there are two adjustment areas, (One adjustment area on the strap is partially hidden.) and they are facing the same way which makes one of the strap adjustments pointing up instead of down when the strap is on your shoulder. The end of the strap sticks up and out. It is a very nice bag, but Dooney & Bourke should correct this flaw.

column13: 5 stars, read my whole review about the \smell\""
column14:
Such pretty boots! My calves are enormous, 18 inches, and they fit great thanks to the lace-up part in the back.
Unfortunately I had to send them back. The color just doesn't match the rest of my cosplay for comic con. My other reason for returning is that while these boots are super sexy, I decided I would regret being on my feet all day for comic con if I wore these.
If you're going to wear them to parties or around the office, I'm sure you'll love them.
Also, other reviewers complained about this infamous "gas smell". As far as the pair I received, NO SMELL at all. It does seem like the company has been listening to the complaints though. On 2 sides of the shoe box, there are plastic-rimmed holes, I assume for ventilation. I suppose this is to ensure that whatever smell results from production doesn't linger on to bother the customer. Hope that helps.
(My rating might not say "amazon verified purchase" because my husband ordered it on his account, but I promise I'm legit :) )

column6: Fallen Chief XI Skate Shoe
column13: Snug fit, classy look, bargain price.
column14: These shoes are slim with a low profile. I bought these in my actual size because of the $15 price tag and they are tight. I'm not returning them. I think the canvas and leather will stretch and loosen after a short time. If you have real wide feet these might not be the best for you.  These came with black and white laces. They are a good looking shoe. I'm not surprised that business men pick up some of these skate shoes to wear to the office. They have a classy look like patent leather shoes.  I intend to skate these once I've broken them in. They are made of both canvas and leather, but it appears that the areas that are subjected to the most abrasion are leather or rubber.  This is my 1st pair of Fallen shoes.  These shipped fast. I ordered on Friday morning and received them Monday afternoon.  I'll edit and update this review once I've broken in and skated these shoes....  Edit/update: I've got about 8 hours of skate time on these shoes and an additional 8 hours of casual wear. They're stretching out a little and I'm really enjoying these on my boards. I kind of like the snug fit for skating. I'm not one to skate with loose shoes or slip ons. As far as wear, all I have is a scuff from Ollie's. I haven't hit the toe leather yet from kickflips and I kickflip frequently.  In closing, if these aren't unbearably tight on your feet, give them some break in time. They're worth it. Also, keep in mind these are skate shoes that are purpose built. They're not ez spirits, or sketchers or new balance. They're not intended to walk the park after bingo or hustle around the office. These shoes are for thrashing the park and grinding the ledges in front of the office.

column6: Etnies Men's Scout MT Skateboard Shoe
column13: Not as constricting as all other skate shoes.  Far more comfortable.  You have the OK to order your normal usual size.
column14: UPDATE2 after a year of use:  I am not an intense skateboarder. I use them as loafers, and they are not the only shoes I wear. After a year, the shoes are showing some wear and tearing beside the little toe, on both shoes.  But they're still going.  The back part tore at the top when I didn't untie my laces properly to remove or put them on.  Most shoes are forgiving of this, not these.  So they are having a beginning stage of falling apart that is taking a long time, and I still like to wear them because of their light weight.  I don't want to replace them, because I'm stubborn and want to get my money's worth, determined to wear them out till they fall apart before I might buy another pair - only in leather next time.   UPDATE1:  I am reducing my rating by one star. shortly after I bought them, the loop at the back, that you grasp to help put them on, came off. Testament to fragile construction. Not happy about that.  Before buying these, I went to a local skate shop in my city to try several brands on. (The clerk at Emp!re was so lazy at first, just chatting with other staff, and then so impolite, that I have absolutely no regrets buying here instead of paying him full retail price).  What I learned, is that Vans are the narrowest, but all brands are extremely narrow and uncomfortable, and while you have to generally go a half size larger, with DC you have to go a full size larger.  To help you better chose the right size, let me give you some background on myself: I wear a size 10 on average. I do have one pair of shoes, for playing soccer, that is 9.5, so I have it snug, as no extra space in front of the toes is desirable. But generally, I buy 10.5 to get a little bit of extra width. I tried these on in the store, and 10.5 fit well, felt light, and it was like you were walking on air. Those were the ones with the large mesh upper.  The ones I ordered are a finer mesh, and are not as comfortable as the ones in the store.  My little toes stick out to the side slightly, as the shoe stretches easily to accomodate your foot's width. In retrospect, I wonder if I shouldn't have ordered a 10, instead of a 10.5, in the case of this model, but I'm thinking that maybe my little toe would be sticking out too far from the side, causing premature wear at that point.  I am generally not impressed with skate shoes. But my well-padded running shoes just don't cut it for skateboarding, and a fall wearing my five-fingers left too much of a gauge on my foot to want to go without skate shoes again.  When I was little, skate shoes, like Converse for example, sold at KMart for $5 a pair. It was what poor parents bought their kids when they couldn't afford better shoes, and us kids hated the experience.  By some stroke of marketing genius, these companies have turned the budget product into a high-priced fasion product with a cult following.  My advice is this (it's what I did), your preferred color might not the the cheapest one there, but your second or third-favorite might be a bargain.  These shoes were about 40 in the size-color combination that I settled on, which is far more reasonable than the 120 they asked in the store for this model. Some of them are under $30, close to 20... but in my size, they were just too ugly. Given they are more comfortable than all other skate shoe models, I think paying about 40 is an OK deal.  But don't go spending 120 on these just because your kid asks for it - none of these skate shoe models are worth that. These are $20 shoes that you accept to pay a little bit extra for on account that they are more comfortable.

column14:
I wish I could give more than 5 stars. All the stars in the world for these shoes! I work full time on concrete floors with chronic knee injuries, and was having some serious pain in my muscles and joints until I bought these. These shoes are definitely not your everyday cute, trendy tennies, but they are comfortable, durable, and offer serious support if you're on your feet all day. The print makes them more interesting than your average work shoe. They also help reduce fatigue! My only complaint is that they are clunky, heavy, and HOT if you're used to wearing lightweight shoes outside of work. The wide, angled toe box took some getting used to, and I still catch my toes on stuff all the time.

I'll confirm that these are easily scuffed and the color does come off if rubbed the wrong way. I don't particularly mind because the print is so varied and spotted to begin with, but if having marks and scrapes on shoes will bother you, it will be better to seek a pair without graphics printed on.

column6: Salomon Men's Speedcross 3 Trail Running Shoe
column14:
This was an impulse buy for tough mudder in Tahoe. Reviews recommended to buy 1/2 size larger than the regular fit, so i did. I'm flat footed and do prefer my shoe to withstand any swelling of the feet. The bottom of the shoe looks like a rally tire and performed nicely on downhill slopes. The non-lace solution had me wondering what would happen if they just snapped, so i found out that the lace replacement kit is ~$10. Pebbles will also find their way exfoliating your feet during the run, so i suggest getting some trail gaiters for ~$25.

The 1 star that i have not included goes to the inner sole. Make sure you cement that sucker down, because it will slip and fold.

On a side note, these are definitely a go to when it comes to hiking.

column6: New Men's Boot Mallory Toe Boot Stretcher
column13: THE BEST OUT THERE, RUGGED AND THEY WORK...ONLY FOR FRONT AND TOE AREA WIDTH, WILL NOT LENGTHEN
column14:
remarkable product. these are only for adding width to the tip of your shoes/boots, but they are super rugged, won't break like the wooden ones, and do a very good job.

you should be able to turn a D width boot/shoe front into a EE width. they do NOT increase length, but give you extra room in the front.

NOTE: any boot manufacturer/boot store will tell you that you cannot stretch the harder leather tip of a boot as they have fiberboard or harder leather underneath the top leather. this is NOT true. you can't stretch the very tip much, but these will in fact be able to not only stretch the front portion of your boot/shoe, but they will expand the very tip to some degree as well.

column6: Skechers Performance Men's Go Run Ride 4 Running Shoe
column13: Converted this skeptical runner/triathlete, will be ordering more.
column14: I was very skeptical that Skechers could make a good running shoe.  I have ran in several of the big well-known traditional running shoes like Asics GT-1000, GT-2000, Cumulus, Brooks, New Balance, etc.  I wanted to move to a low heel drop cushion shoe like the Hoka One One, but they were expensive.  On forums I read that the Skechers Go Run Ride was pretty similar to the Hoka Bondi, but costs literally 1/2 the price.  I had to try them.  I only have about 25 miles on them and ran one Olympic triathlon (10k run) race in these so far and I'm really impressed.  They are light and very comfortable.  I was afraid the EVA sole would feel squishy and marshmallowy but it does not, it's cushioned but positive and firm and balanced in absorbing any impact.  Because the sole is softer foam, you can feel rough surfaces more so than some other shoes.  These shoes are responsive and feel like they push back on your foot a bit as you push off.  The toe box is wider than Asics which feels good, your foot can naturally spread out.  Breathable uppers keeps them feeling light and airy.  The difference in heel drop is noticeable compared to a traditional "crash pad" heel.  It encourages you to run with better form and I like it.  I will be ordering more of these and will be rotating through them.  I'm very pleased.  The sizing is close to "real" shoe size, if anything a tad bigger than labelled.  Order at least 1/2 if not a full size smaller than Asics.  I wear a 10.5 - 11 in GT-2000's but a 10 in these Skechers feels good (with the insole installed (without the insole I might even go down to a 9.5).  The liner is nice and could be worn sockless.  With the softer foam sole I anticipate lower mileage but other reviews seem to say they last just as well as other shoes because support and foam will usually break down before the soles wear out anyway.  Regardless, at this price, they could last a lot less and still be a great value.

column6: NUU Women's Insight Walking Shoes
column13: Surprisingly well-made, true to size, and ultra-comfortable ...
column14:
This is a marvelously comfortable pair of slip-on shoes that are true to fit. Many times I‚Äôve attempted to purchase clothing or shoes online only to be sorely disappointed because the sizing was off (usually too small). These are listed both in men‚Äôs and women‚Äôs sizes so selection is easy. They aren‚Äôt narrow by any means and certainly didn‚Äôt cramp my feet. I recently purchased a pair of Merrells and they were a bit on the narrow side.

The design is an unusual one with reproductions of an assortment of Americana, ephemera that was rather interesting to say the least. In one corner I even found a reproduction of an old Disneyland ticket advertising Main Street and Fantasyland. Distinctive, but solely a matter of taste I suppose. My daughter-in-law took one look at them and nixed the style.

I‚Äôm not particularly enamored with the design, but were this in a plain color or age-appropriate design, I‚Äôd buy them in a minute. These, for me at least, would be perfect for beachwear or casual wear. The support is excellent and I do like the slip-on style. So very comfortable and easy to wear. They are 70s and 80s retro, but don‚Äôt quite have their target audience perfected with that design.

How well are they made? Surprisingly well made and not at all cheap. There‚Äôs piping around the sole and top line. There‚Äôs an elasticized band on either side which make them easy to slip on. The insole is quite cushy, comfortable, and the front part is sewn in a pattern that will keep them from disintegrating or falling out. The designer sole is non-slip with a cool looking tree-like design with roots. Nope, I don‚Äôt like the design, but these slip-on shoes are very well-made and ultra comfortable.

Sample provided for review.

column14: These shoes are very pretty and i really like them, but there are a couple of issues with them. First, the navy shoes are not navy. I love that color so I'll wear them with other things but they definitely don't work with my navy blue outfits so i still have to find a pair of navy shoes. Secondly, the straps across the toes are uncomfortable and i had to add foam padding to the underside. But they are so attractive and the arch support and sole are so comfortable, i still love the shoes and have to give them 4 stars!  One more thing - i have a true AA foot, but the adjustable strap across the toes fits just right. That is, when i fasten the velcro of the strap across the toes to fit me, the edges of the top and bottom strips align exactly, with no excess hanging over. Because of that i believe these shoes are a bit narrow across the toes...I have a lot of B width shoes with velcro straps, and with all of them i have at least 1" of excess strap when i align the velcro across toes. that works great for me but may not work for others. column6: ECCO Men's Biom Golf Shoe
column14: I have played about 5 rounds in these shoes and also worn them on the range. On the range they fit perfectly and feel great. On the course, I consistently get blisters on the heels on both feet and end up limping by around the 4th hole. I have to put band aids under my socks in order to finish the round. I have tried to work out why this happens - they fit perfectly and are the correct size - and worked out that the blisters are exactly the spot where the leather of the upper heel joins with the soft padding at the top of the shoe. The join creates a bump at the back of the shoe which is causing the blisters. In the past I wore less fashionable and cheaper Footjoys and had no problems with them. I really regret being swayed by the looks of these $200 plus shoes as they have proved to be very dissapointing. I would return them if I could - and should have done so after my first round in them - but keep hoping that they would wear in. They haven't!

column13: These run tight across the foot, but are cushy - serves the need to cushion injured foot
column14: I wear a 6.5 wide, and to get these to work, had to order the women's Equivalent size 9. Yes, the size 9 to get a fit for 6.5 wide.  This means they are a bit long on my foot.  I originally ordered them in the women's equivalent size 8 As other reviewers mentioned that these ran small, but they were still way too tight across the foot.  The longer length also allowed me to get my heel in a better place on the sole of the shoe.  When the foot sits on the actual heel cup, there is a tendency to feel like you are pitching backwards.  All in all, I needed the shoes to help recover from a foot injury, these have a very cushy feel that is comforting to the foot, yet provide very good arch support.  In the end they serve the purpose, but the sizing is weirder than weird, and seems the option of wider widths would really help level it out.  Also, these sandals work much better without socks.  Because of the rubbery material they are made of, it is hard to get a sock to slide into the sandal without getting stretched or bunching up.

column14:
Great hiking boots. I wore these on an easy hike to break them in, but I didn't even really need to. The arch support feels fantastic. I like that my ankles felt supported and there was no blisters or rubbing anywhere. I am so happy with these.

For the size, I was confused as to which one would be good for me. I wear a size 7-7.5 depending on the shoe. I purchased both the size 7.5 and 8 in these boots. The 8 was a little too loose, even with thick socks. The 7.5 was perfect. It was loose enough to have some wiggle room, but they felt secure on my feet. I do have narrow feet and I thought the 8 were too wide.

Overall, I am very happy on my Keen hiking boots and will purchase these again when my pair breaks down.

column6: Mens Wave Water Shoes Aqua Socks
column13: Not as good as I read here
column14:
There are both design and implementation issues with these shoes. They would be appropriate for a weekend getaway where you wanted to throw them away afterward providing you were walking only short distances.

Design
- The sole is satisfactory and should protect from rocks, including side brushes
- The enclosure does not tighten the overall shoe like laces or velcro would, instead it tightens the top around your ankle. That keeps the shoe from coming off but if you tighten it for significant walking you'd better expect lines on the ankle and pain later
- The tightening ball does not really keep the string tight when wet
- The ball bounces against the back of the ankle when the string is wet

Implementation
- Sole is good in implementation as well as design. No real issues with the top netting
- The glue attaching the very thin foam to the inside of the shoe was faulty. The foam completely detached after a day and let the foam slide which it did. Removing the foam exposes your feet to the inside stitching and eliminates all cushion.

Overall - get something else. Better options are available at similarly low cost.

column6: Birkenstock Women's Arizona  Birko-Flo Sandals
column14:
These shoes saved me. I had developed planter fasciitis and nothing seemed to relieve the pain. I got to the point where I thought about every step I was going to take and I took as few steps as possible. Not a good position to be in. I had an old pair of Birkenstocks (25 years old) that were seriously broken down, yet even in horrible condition were better than anything else I had. I ordered these with the hope that they would offer a bit more relief than the old ones and they did. They are wonderful. I wear them every where, every day, all day. I have developed a callous where the back strap (closest to the ankle) rubs but it never hurt or blistered. I do not have any pain in my heel when I wear these sandals. They have been great.
It was difficult for me at first to make them my full time shoes because of their expense, but slipping them on whenever I get up is now just my daily routine like taking my vitamins.

column6: Damero Genuine Leather Messenger Bag Women Cross body Satchel Tote (10.5 inch, Brown)
column13: Where do I start about how much I love his bag
column14:
Where do I start about how much I love his bag? It's so classy and stylish. I got the one in the brown/tan leather color. The bag comes in a pristine condition and arrives within a week. The strap is packed inside the bag. The length of the strap can be adjusted as desired using the buckle. The is strap on top the bag also if you want to carry it in your hand instead of like a cross-body bag. The are buckle accents on the front of the bag as well. No pockets on outside to keep the design simple. The flap closes with 2 magnetic buttons in the front. There is pocket in the front and then the main compartment. There is a zipped small hidden pocket inside and card slots as well. The leather is of amazing quality. It smooth and stitched together nice and neat. You can pair this bag with any color of dress for any occasion.
Sample provided without any obligations.

column6: Riverberry Women's Gaby Pointed Closed Toe Stiletto Pump Heels
column14:
I just love the Riverberry brand! These are the Gaby Shoes in Grey Snake. They have a 4 1/2 inch heal with extra heel tips! No one ever included extra heel tips, so an added bonus. I got a size 6.5 and it's a perfect fit. The color is fantastic and well made. Looks like other expensive brands for a not so expensive price! The bottom is a wood grain like color that goes well with the snake skin and compliments the shoe. I cannot wait to wear these on date nights- let the dancing commence. The lining is not cushioned but that is an easy fix with a padded insert you can find anywhere. I love these heels so much I want other colors. Highly recommended by this high heel shoe lover.
I did receive this product at a 50% discount for my honest unbiased review.

column14:

column6: PUMA Women's Asha Alt 2 Slip-On Sneaker
column14:
I've been buying Puma's for years. I have to say I'm not sure what design has been changed but these are the best pair I've ever owned.
First and foremost, the aesthetic appeal. I'm one who doesn't really care what my "comfy" shoes look like. I'm wearing them because i want to be able to walk long distances, not because they're cute. However these surpass expectation. I get several compliments on them, and the color is bright yet subdued enough that they're easy to match to.
I'm a fan of slip ons, so these are really easy to throw on and go. The most surprising thing about these though is i can actually RUN in them! Yes, run at speed. Without worrying about one flying off. They hold up on different terrains okay (obviously not recommended for rocky terrain, but if you're looking for shoes for rocky terrain and you wound up here, you may want to investigate your hobby further), and even do a decent job crossing slick surfaces while wet.
The main reason I purchased these was for a family vacation to disneyland. In my first true day of wearing them, my pedometer had 18 miles on it before my phone died. I was able to get up and do the exact same thing the next day. These shoes provided excellent support and have maintained the comfort.

I will be buying future pairs in different colors as these are the best investment in my closet I've made.

column13: I have flat feet and I bought into the philosophy ...

The problem I always encountered was that the extra arch support would cause high pressure points on the arches and after a few miles, blister city.  After seeing a sports doctor and getting pointed to a runners shoe store with very knowledgable staff, I got setup with these shoes, which basically have minimal arch support and are the right width for my feet.  Blisters are history and I've gone from suffering through 5k's to doing half-marathons without issue.

column6: Pearl Izumi Men's EM Road N3 Running Shoe
column14: The N3 has a very smooth transition from heel to toe makes this shoe feel fast, even though it is a heavy 11.7oz (size9). The seamless upper is very comfortable. And it looks very good!  I've run about 60k in these shoes thus far. The upper is amazing. Holds the feet well like a glove, yet wide in the forefoot to allow for toe splay. The transition is very smooth and inforesee this is a good shoe for long races up to a marathon. Have tried them on light trails and grip is good enough, but with Rocky paths, the shoe tends to flex too much.  After only 60k, the heel wear is significant. Tradeoff for the cushioning and smooth heel to toe transition perhaps.

column6: FASH Limited Cross-body Handbag, Dual Handle, One Size
column14:
I‚Äôm a grad student who also works on campus, so I needed a bag that would carry all my school stuff but also look professional. I have been attracted to the dome shaped satchels for quite some time, and was over the moon when I saw this bag for the price.

The shape is very clean and modern. It is also well made and study, and is big enough to hold my chromebook (this is a smaller laptop, not certain if the Macbook would fit) and all my books and notebooks for class. The straps are big enough that I can easily loop my arm through it and carry it even up on my shoulder comfortably. It comes with an attachable/detachable crossbody strap as well. The inside lining is decently done (seems to be a cheaper material, but not a big deal at all for me) and does come with additional sewn in pockets for your phone, etc.

Overall, I am completely in love, as this bag fulfills all my needs for school and work. This bag looks like a designer-brand and has the durability of one, yet is at an incredible price. I even bought a second bag as a back up, and may additionally splurge on the brown bag. :)

column6: MICHAEL Michael Kors Jet Set Top-Zip Tote
column14: I love everything about this bag, and I've received many compliments on it just in the first week. The color of it and the clean lines go with everything from professional outfits to casual weekend looks. For me though, looks don't matter much if the functionality isn't there. I'm happy to report this purse is not only beautiful, but thoughtfully put together for optimal organization. The two pockets on the outside of the purse are deep but quite tight, so they are not ideal for keeping a cell phone or keys in as I thought they might be. You could certainly use them for that, but I would worry that the pockets would stretch out and cause the bag to wear more quickly. However, do not despair. Inside there is a large zippered pouch on one side, and dual pockets on either side of the bag. One side has two pockets that are cell-phone sized and can easily accommodate any device. The other side has one slightly smaller pocket and one slightly bigger pocket. The larger one is perfect for car keys, while I use the small one for lip glosses and such. No more rummaging around for those pesky smaller items that seem to fall into the mysterious bermuda triangle that live in all tote purses. Thank you to the practical geniuses at Michael Kors for your generous use of purse pockets!! The remaining space in the purse can easily fit a tablet or book along with all the other necessities. I am a little concerned by some of the other reviewers who reported straps breaking, but they appear to be well constructed and considering everything this bag has to offer, I am willing to take the risk.

column13: Ordering a second pair for backup.
column14:
These are my new favorite shoes. My feet are, shall we say, sensitive - I can get a blister walking 25 feet with the world's tiniest pebble in my shoe. Two years ago my family went to Disneyland and by the end of the first day I had several blisters from wearing cheap shoes. I bought these in anticipation of another theme park visit, this time with tons of hills (Silver Dollar City). The shoes felt broken in the minute I put them on. We put on 5+ miles per day for 4 days and my feet gave me absolutely no trouble.

I am dealing with the early stages of plantar fasciitis and I think these shoes are really going to help prevent further pain. They are soft, supportive and breathable. I love them.

column14:
This is my 5th pair of Birkenstock Gizeh. I have developed arthritis in my midfoot area. Had surgery, still no relief. I can wear these shoes all day. Once you find the right size Birkenstock, you will always be able to order the same size in any style.These are amazing, very trendy right now, but will stay in style forever. Might be a good idea to go to a Birkenstock retailer and be properly fitted. I hear people complain about their Birks, saying they "aren't all that". Come to find out they are wearing the wrong size, either too narrow or too short.
I love this style. I'm a flip flop person, so this particular style ticks that box, and yet adds a lot of style to ANY outfit. Linen skirts, jeans, linen pants, shorts. You name it, I wear Birks with it. I will keep buying them as new colors and materials are coming out with each season.

column6: Merrell Women's All Out Blaze Hiking Shoe
column13: Good, roomy fit in a compact shoe.
column14: I will have to update this review after my hiking trip, but so far these shoes were the best fit out of the 4 pairs that I ordered. They are a little wide, but the laces can be tightened to make them fit around the foot while still having lots of room in the toe box, which is important for up and downhill hiking. They are also surprising compact for how roomy they are. They look small on your feet, but provide lots of space inside. Even though there are no insoles in these shoes, they have a pretty high arch support, and are also roomy enough that you could add your own insole if you wanted. I ordered my street size and they fit fine.

column13: They are extremely comfortable and \cushiony\" and good for long runs"
column14: I've been wearing Asics for 25+ years since high school track days. I've tried other brands but always come back to Asics. These are the top-of-the-line Nimbus and I guess what makes them top is they have the most cushion, which is what I wanted. I use these for training and racing and usually put about 30~40 miles of running in per week training and racing half and full Ironman (13.1~26.2 miles). I have several pairs of Nimbus shoes that I rotate and these are one of them. They are extremely comfortable and "cushiony" and good for long runs. Since they are very expensive, I generally just buy 1 or 2 models back and don't worry about the color, just get the cheapest in my size, that will save you a few bucks. I have also used the "Kayano" model but feel the Nimbus have more cushion and feel better than the Kayano's (for me).

column6: ASICS Men's Gel Noosa Tri 9 Running Shoe
column13: I actually posted the fastest transition times in a triathlon with these things (T2 / T1+T2)
column14:
I ended up picking up these shoes for my short distance road races and triathlons and figured I'd post a review now that I've used them for a sprint triathlon.

Although I had trained and run in more structured shoes for years (mostly nimbus & cumulus), I figured now that my weight was getting low enough, a smaller profile and less structured shoe may give me a bit more speed despite their reduction in support.

True to their purpose, they came with both the elastics, and regular laces. The elastics were initially a bit tight, so I switched over to laces until I needed to race in the shoes, at which point the extra grip from the elastic helped as I opted to go sockless for my race.

When training with them for my speedwork days & pace runs, the support was definitely reduced vs. my heavier duty shoes, and I was feeling rocks more when running on trails. Still, the lighter weight helped my pickup, and seemed to help with speed.

For my first triathlon with them, I was stuck in a city without my bike, and true to the "swim, bike, run" words plastered all over the shoe design, I actually used them for both the bike & run. I'm pretty sure that the USAT wouldn't approve them for the swim leg anyhow.

Flying out of the swim, I very quickly slid the shoes on without socks, strapped on my helmet, put on my sunglasses and exited the transition area, posting a time within 8 seconds of the T1 leader (who likely just did a flying bike start with clipless pedals clipped in). For the ride, with track pedals and half clips, they soles held up despite hammering pretty hard on my climbs, although these aren't as rigid as normal bike shoes.

Coming out of the bike, my feet were dry (as they seemed to air out on the ride) and I just opted to keep the shoes on without socks, racked my bike & helmet, sprinting out of T2, and posted the fastest transition time out of the 250 competitors in my race (and fastest combined transition time). Racing the 5K in them went pretty well, as I posted a faster pace/time than my pre triathlon 5 mile race. Still, by the end of the 5k, I could tell the bottom of my feet weren't as happy due to the limited support, and I don't think a marathon is in the shoes' future.

In short, they actually work pretty well for triathlons (even sockless), and the lighter weight/lower profile design seemed to help with speed.

column6: Merrell Men's Moab Ventilator Hiking Shoe
column13: Durable hiking shoe except for the adhesive between the outersole and midsole
column14:
I've had these Moab Ventilators for about five years now. They run about half a size to a size too small. I have these in size 10W but I normally wear a 9.5EE, and they are tight and snug all around. However I usually wear hiking shoes with half an inch allowance between my toes and the toe box, so these will be quite constricted with thick socks(but manageable using thin socks).

The color and styling is nice, and the uppers are very durable (no stitching is falling apart). The Vibram sole is also durable (wear and tear also minimal). But the biggest gripe I have (as well as other Merrell hiking shoes with Vibram soles) is that the adhesive that glues the outersole and the midsole deteriorates over time, and completely separates from the shoe. One pair I had took less than 3 years to do so, this Moab Ventilator managed a good five years. They can still be used provided you stick back the Vibram outersole using Shoe Goo, and they will likely last at least another year or two.

This particular pair is not waterproofed (no Goretex or similar inner membrane), so water seeps into the sock after a downpour. I would recommend the Goretex variant of the Moab Ventilator and that I will rate 5 stars. But for this one, 4 stars means it is good enough and worth your money over the long haul.

column6: Pacific Trail Women's Tioga Walking Shoe
column14: I bought these shoes for an upcoming 2 day hiking trip. I was pleasantly surprised that for both of the days that they provided ample support for my feet. The first day was a fairly flat and easy 7 mile hike, and the second day was an 11 mile hike with both uphill and downhill inclines. I was worried that these shoes would not be of very good quality, since I bought them for $45 and the padding seemed a bit thin, but I have walked away without any blisters or foot soreness. As for the fit of the shoe it was not true to my actual size. Normally I wear a size 7.5 to 8. I ended up buying a size 7, although a size 6.5 fit my foot too. I decided to go with a 7 in order to allow for my feet to swell during my hike. The only real issue that I have with these shoes is that the traction on the front of the shoe is already peeling away from the shoe. Overall this shoe was a good investment for the price. I am sure there are better quality shoes out there, but just for doing casual hiking I think that these suffice.

column6: Hoka One Men's Clifton 2
column14: I didn't buy the shoes on Amazon, but I'm reviewing them just the same. I have about 40 miles in them so far and it's all trail work. The trails have been a mixture of bone dry and wet . The shoes have performed fantasticly  in all the conditions that I have thrown at them. The feel of the shoes on the trail is very unique to me.  You definitely get that feeling of running on a cloud, but with no rock plate in the shoe you can definitely feel the terrain under your feet. So if you hit a sharp rock you're going to definitely  through the shoe. Not in a bad way but you definitely get more trail feel with the shoe that I have with any of the other trail shoes I have used. That would include the hoka  Stinson Trail, Challenger ATR, and Sockin he Peregrin four Challenger ATR, and saucony peregrine 4's.  If you're looking for the hoka  feel in a decently lightweight running shoe with very good off-road traction this would be the shoe to look very closely at

column6: Wolverine Men's Cabor Waterproof 6-Inch Work Boot
column13: Looks great complements about them all the time when new
column14:
Have had these for a year now.
Pros:
Looks great complements about them all the time when new. Sole being fused there has been zero pull away which is amazing after a year. Epx feels great. I work 8 to 18 hours a day standing on cement floor and these boots are amazingly comfortable the whole time. Truly keeps water and dirt out. Reasonably light weight for a reinforced toe boot. Great non slip soles.

Cons-
The leather on the toe got cut and scratched really easily in only a couple weeks detracting from the appearance, the lace hooks at the top would have been better if they were riveted on eyelets like the rest of the boot or regular eyelets. The hooks catch on pants and other things at work and are a hazard at times.

Note I took these hiking one time to see how these would do. I know they are work boots but was an experiment.
Waterproof - yes
Dirt - kept dirt and rocks out
Fatigue - comfortable but noticeably too heavy for hiking in the end
Support - great felt excellent around ankles
Traction - great never slipped on any terrain.

Even with the cons in normal work situations I would say 5 stars and I hope to see this line continue with small improvements. I would but again.

column6: Timberland PRO Men's Pitboss 6\ Soft-Toe Boot"
column13: A very well made pair of boots.
column14:
I am a meat cutter and I am standing 8 hours per day.
I have tried waterproof hikers and various work-boots and usually bought whatever was on sale.
This was usually a mistake
Between the work environment, the liquid purge from the beef and pork that hits your shoes and
cleaning with de-greaser and hot water, I usually killed every pair within 12 months or less.
So far these boots are the most comfortable I have ever worn.
I get calluses and these boot do a great job of protecting your feet and cushioning your step.
If they slide around your ankle at the top and chafe, then just tie them better so they don't move.
They are warm and durable. I already scuffed them and have a few stains on them which
is a shame because they are a great looking pair of boots.
I coated them with silicone spray a couple of times already so they resist further stains and water.
So far they are doing great.
I would recommend them.

column13: Never wore heels before...now I can't take them off.
column14:
Never wore heels before...now I can't take them off.

I would never have guessed that a sport shoe company like Teva would ever venture into heels, but these are brilliant. I have never worn heels (though I like them) because I refuse to have sore feet that can't walk normally. These are game changers. They are extremely comfortable, stylish, the straps are real leather (YAY) and the footbed is some weird version crossover that seems to be a crossover of rubber / polymer / cork (I'm grasping here and making that part up as I go along...it's definitely man-made)...but it's firm enough to hold your weight, but seems to absorb the impact (at least, I never feel any impact). My feet don't get tired, I can walk as much as I want and feel great. (Generally, if I can walk, I will; I don't like moving my car for every errand).

I will say that on a recent tourist trip, I did not take these and chose the flat, sport shoe Tevas, but all-day sightseeing on cobblestones lugging camera, etc. seemed to be a fools errand in any heels.

If you need the support this is a great shoe!

column6: Baggallini Messenger Bagg BS Convertible Cross-Body Bag
column13: A very nice bag concept but could use a few improvements.
column14:
I think this is a great bag in general . The one I received does not have the mesh shown in the picture for the middle pocket but that one is an older model and the newer model that i received had a solid lining. This bag does not provide any secure type locking system or rfid pockets so maybe not ideal for travel. Easily fits more than you can imagine including a tablet but there is no padding ( might make it heavier). If you overload, although the wide strap helps, you might want to buy those wrap cushions designed for backpacks. Front strap pocket ok but too small for a phone or oversized sunglasses. Maybe could be used for a credit card wallet.

What I liked:
-Multi pockets
-lightweight
-water resistance
-attractive
-wide adjustable strap
-good size without being too small or large
-water bottle pocket ( although very tight squeeze for 16 oz bottle)
-side pocket for sunglasses

What could be improved:
-needs to have rfid pockets and maybe some toggle closure for more security.
-Zippers don't always glide easily so not sure about longevity
-Lining in middle pocket is taller than zipper so gets caught every time ( maybe I got a defective one)
- have at least one side zip pocket instead of all top entry ( slings twist around so you can easily access and most have a side entry pocket which makes it easy to leave the bag on your body while you access a pocket)
-would be nice if large pocket had a divider for more organization.
-Needs some updating for a quick access phone pocket that also fits larger phones (like the hidden quick grab ones that most of the travelon bags have)
-Wish strap could be used in either direction

I will be sending mine back because of the lining/zipper problem. I may try another or look for one that is close to this with more of the wish list features I listed above.

column6: KEEN Women's Rose Sandal
column14:
These Rose sandals are my 6th pair of Keens and are the only uncomfortable pair. Although these sandals are fairly cute, the strap is a problem for 3 reasons.
1) I have a higher instep and these sandals don‚Äôt stretch enough to accommodate.
2) I really dislike Velcro, and it is completely unnecessary for these sandals.
3) Straps that come this high up one‚Äôs foot look juvenile and shorten the look of the leg.

I made some adjustments to improve the fit. However, I wish Keen would improve the design by moving the strap lower on the foot (to hit in the same spot as the Venice sandals) and remove the Velcro.

My revamp: I used a seam ripper to remove the grosgrain ribbon and the attached Velcro. This revealed a strip of microfiber fabric that had been sewn to the ankle strap, which had reduced the stretchiness of the strap. As a precaution, I sewed the fabric to the strap at the base, and then I trimmed it. Sewing down the fabric is probably unnecessary as it doesn‚Äôt seem to fray, but I wanted to be safe.

If the strap still bothers me, I will cut it off entirely. The sandals stay on well enough without it.

column6: Crocs Women's Cleo Croslite Sandals
column14: I discovered this model of Crocs 5 years ago, after foot surgery, this was the most comfortable footwear I could wear. I have bought a new pair every year since. I have tried many newer models of Crocs slippers since, and was always disappointed. This design is perfect. The swivelling strap keeps them on, and having just 2 straps is not causing blisters even if I go for a 10Km hike. New models come with 3 straps, or not swivelling 2nd strap, flatter, less arch supporting soles, heels etc, all inferior to this old model. The only problem is that it is not available in stores anymore in Canada.

column13: This is a good pair overall
column14:
This is a good pair overall. I've only had a chance to wear them once in the rain, however my feet were dry as this was the sole purpose of the purchase.

The only downside is that these shoes fit narrower than the average. I originally bought a regular width and they were very tight around the inside and outside of the toes. I returned them right away as I wasn't very confident that the leather could stretch enough with time for the pair to be comfortable. I bought the 2E width in its' place and they're comfortable for the casual style of the shoe. Something to think about if you're within outside borderline average width.

This pair might be able to be worn all day depending on the person, if you're on your feet all day it may not be enough. More so this is a pair that gets you to and from wherever you're going without getting your feet wet nor having to spend twice the amount of money for similar style and quality- while also not having to look like the Gordon's Fisherman from the commercials.

Overall, a good pair for the money spent.

Advice: If you ride smooth and gentle, go for this shoes, they are great. If you ride harsh terrain or dh/4x/enduro racing, go for the other brands.

column6: Timberland White Ledge Men's Waterproof Boot
column13: Two sets of boots in a row which were defective. What a shame.
column14: I'm not sure what's going on with these boots. I ordered a pair a couple weeks ago and the first day I wore them I noticed a wet spot on the left boot just in front of the laces on the inside of the boot. I figured I dripped on them after washing my hands. The spot didn't go away though, in fact it got larger as the day went on. That exact little spot... I figured I'd make sure it dried up over night and I'd have a look the next day. Same thing happened. I thought it was pretty weird. Maybe there's a moisture barrier in there or something that wasn't stitched properly, maybe that little spot wasn't treated properly during the production, who knows? I set up an exchange and got a new pair which arrived today. THE SAME EXACT THING HAPPENED. SAME LEFT BOOT! I've never experienced this before but it's just plain weird. This time I snagged a picture to show what was going on here. I'm guessing there is a whole boat load of these shoes produced in the same place that have the same defect. It's a shame but I guess I wasn't meant to have these boots. The sad thing is now I have two wasted trips to the UPS store. After paying over 100 bucks for the boots and more than 2 weeks later I don't have a pair that's satisfactory for keeping and I've wasted gas going back to the UPS shop to send them back. Quite dissatisfied.

column13: Looks good, lightweight, easy to use.
column14: I'd never heard of this brand of bag before I bought this, and usually I go for a leather-type handbag. This was somewhat of a departure from that preference, but having read some really great reviews on how lightweight these bags are, and how well they hold up, I thought I'd give it a shot. So far it has exceeded my expectations, and the reviewers are right. It is very lightweight and sturdy. I really like the feel of the fabric, and love all the pockets - fantastic way to organized everything! I think the thing I appreciate the most is the lovely bright yellow interior that makes finding things that go hiding in the deepest recesses of your bag a snap. The strap is ultra-adjustable, so I can have it longer for cross-body style, or shorter for just over-the-shoulder or hand carry. The only very small complaint is that the slider buckle on the strap is slippery and doesn't hold its position well for the length selected. I can probably figure out a work-around for that problem pretty easily, though. I just really like this bag!

column13: They felt great in the store so I decided to pick them ...
column14:
Bought these on sale from a Nike factory outlet. They felt great in the store so I decided to pick them up. After having played on them for a few weeks I began developing shin splints and my feet really hurt sometimes after playing. I've had splints before so I won't say that I got them only from this shoe, could just be coincidental timing. I certainly know that the sore feet specifically in the ball/toe area are from these shoes though as when i switch back to my other shoes I don't get the same pains.

I have flat, narrow feet so perhaps it is just for my specific foot type, but I would say if you fall into that category as well, you should probably steer clear of this shoe. I'm already looking into buying another pair of sneakers and just eating the $50 I paid for these.

column6: Timberland PRO Men's 40008 Mudsill Low Steel-Toe Lace-Up
column14:
I have tried many work shoes that have never lasted more than a year before they are ready to throw out. But the Timberland Pro Mudsill shoes are the best I personally have owned and worn. These are worn 5-6 days a week, 8 to 10 hours a day in a machine shop environment where there is the constant threat of spilled oil or a dropped piece of steel and they do quite well.

I am now on my second pair of Timberland Pros. The first pair are over 2 years old (purchased May of 2013) and have developed noticeable wearing mainly in the heel and toe areas. Wear on the inside is better than expected. Also, I have not yet had to replace the shoe strings. Though I am now on my second pair, the first pair are by no means ready to throw away. They are still usable for yard work. The quality of construction is evident in the workmanship of the product.

I wear a size 10.5 wide. They fit as expected and are quite comfortable once broken in. Wearing these shoes all day means sweaty feet so I use the bamboo charcoal packets to absorb the odor and prevent bacteria from forming. I am very happy with the product and will of course purchase these again.

column6: Skechers for Work Men's Foreman Concore Steel-Toe Boot
column14:
I have that goofy foot side. A little wide but not "WIDE". It makes standard sizes too tight and wide sizes too loose. I have started wearing orthotic inserts to help with Plantar Fasciitis and it makes standard shoes way too tight. I use the inserts and it made these boots fit just right (10 1/2 wide).
These boots are some of the best I have purchased in a long time. very comfortable from the first day and getting better. They stay tied and came with premium woven laces. Nice grip on the bottom, great for working on a ladder.
If I had one thing I would change it would be the tongue. I would make it about 1/2" taller as it just covers the top lace without using the gusset's. I never use the gussets so it is not a problem for me but may for someone who uses the gussets. I will keep my eye open for these in the non steel toe model as I would like to try them for off-site use.

I read the sizing reviews before I ordered and therefore ordered the next size up, from where I should have. I'm glad I did.

column6: Johnston & Murphy Men's Vauter Tassel Loafer
column14:
I hate shopping for shoes in stores, and this was my first purchase of Johnston & Murphy shoes on-line. (I bought these in August 2014.)

Since I had purchased Johnston & Murphy shoes before, and know my size, I took a gamble with Amazon. I bought the tan version of this shoe. These shoes look great and fit me perfectly - there were no problems at all, straight out of the box and took no time to "break in". I wear them a couple of times a week with dress clothes for work. When they are "off duty", I use cedar wood shoe trees to help them keep their shape and fit. I've still got some older Johnston & Murphy loafers (black) that are at least 10 years old, and that have been re-soled and re-heeled probably half a dozen times. The uppers still look good, so I'm expecting the same with these shoes. Frankly, I do not see any decrease in the quality of the leather or construction.

column13: Not a wide enough size available
column14: These are the most awesome boot ever.  We gather cattle in rough terrain.  This involves lots of walking.  This boot supports my foot well.  However, I can no longer wear the boot.  I wear 6.5 D in Womens.  NO ONE makes this size in a boot.  I have a high arch, and need a lot of room for my toes.  Years of wearing boots that aren't quite wide enough (no, getting a 7 instead doesn't work.  No, a 6.5 CD is not the same as a 6.5D) has given me metatarsalgia.  Men's boots would have to come in size 4.5 and they don't.  Boys' boots do not have room in them for a high arch, and you can't get this size anyway.  If these boots came in a size 6.5D, I would never buy a different boot ever.  As it is, I am still looking.

(there is a snap loop on the back for the strap, making it into a back pack). column6: EM TRI N 2
column13: Has a lot of good qualities but really a snug fit that causes problems on longer runs.
column14:
I really wanted to like these shoes but got a full size up from what I wear and they were still very tight. The lock laces did not allow me to let much out, so with the laces all the way released, it was still a tight fit. They did stay in place, no heel slippage. Had really good foot support, great color.
A bit heavier than the N1.
Right out the box they were hard to get on, even ordering a size up. There was a lot of pressure on the top of my foot and my toes. I would have preferred a bit of wiggle room. Walked in them on day one with no socks...had to put socks on after about two hours as they started to rub the top of my foot. The shoes feel heavy compare to the N1, but provided better impact cushioning so can't fault that.
With thin socks they felt better, but still really tight.
The next day I ran three miles in them. They were okay. They had great traction, a big improvement over the N1. They gripped the road without suctioning my foot to the ground and slowing me down. They handled off road well, but were unbalanced in the grass and made it hard to feel the ground so had to be really careful how I put my foot down... they did great on gravel and dirt, but handled the road best.
The day after that I could not wear them without socks.
The heel rest is really stiff, but it did not bother my foot and I tend to be very sensitive to this, so that surprised me.
Wore them on short runs for a week and they were okay, but still not really comfortable to wear.
After a week I took them on a 12 mile run and they really rubbed my toes (my second toe is longer than my big toe so it took most of the wear and actually started to hurt forcing me to walk the next mile and a half and finally give up.
I keep hoping they will loosen up like the N1 s did, but it took them six months to start to feel more comfortable and I haven't got that much time to break these in before the next long race, so am a bit disappointed on the fit. I really feel like I needed to go up two sizes.
For short runs I think these shoes will do, but for long runs, they put too much pressure on my toes and feel cramped in the toe box.
So, the negatives... tight fit, puts pressure on toes and upper foot without much space to release it, heel box is a bit too stiff with a bit too much padding if you are used to a more minimalist shoe.
Positives - has great traction and turn over, making it easy to take long strides, protects feet from pounding, great color and design, easy to pull on and fits snugly, has a good amount of upper ventilation and relatively lightweight compared to other model shoes.

column14: I love these! I was looking for a set of good winter boots, since I walk everywhere, and I live in chilly New England. I actually wear these as all purpose boots, because they are so pretty, and go with almost everything! They kept my feet warm and dry, when it was 15 below zero, with snow up to my waist. Withstood hours of snow shoveling, walking in cold and wet weather. As other have said, the caveat is the Velcro closure above the zippers on the inside of the boot. They're weak, and fiddly, and don't do much. It does make the top of the boot on the inside of the leg a bit floppy, as the leather gives way where the Velcro cuts in. Although I don't have skinny calves, by any stretch of the imagination, they were still a bit loose at the top, closed all of the way. It did help, however, when wearing layers of leggings or pants, on the really cold days, because there was always room to tuck them into the top of the boots, without having to worry about them closing. They fit really nice, too. I have big feet (10-11 in women, depending), and they're also a bit wide. These fit perfectly, right out the box. I was impressed! All in all, these are fabulous, and I would recommend them.

column6: Nike Nike Fingertrap Max Mens Cross Training Shoes Grey New In Box
column13: Purchased for looks, pleasantly surprised by performance
column14:
Currently my favorite shoes for all-day comfort. I love the sock-like grip of the shoe, the air max heel, and unique design of the shoes.

The biggest benefit I've seen is when wearing these to theme parks like Disneyland. I have an annual pass and have tried several different shoes, but the fingertraps have always left my feet feeling great after 8-10 hour days of walking around plus waiting in line. When I know I'm in for a long day, I always pick these out from my collection of 10+ pairs of shoes.

My second favorites are my flyknit free 4.0, which are great for short, 2-4 hour outings but not so much for longer days. Once these fingertraps are worn out, I might be trying the flyknit air max to get the best of both worlds. That price tag is quite steep though and would likely steer me elsewhere!

I don't use these for working out since I mostly lift (I use Adidas Adipowers), but for sports activities minus basketball, these would be my go-to. The grip is amazing for simply walking around and I love hearing the sticky grip sound when walking around on pavement.

I also have Skechers walking shoes with memory foam inside, but those actually left my feet in pain after ~4 hours. Those are collecting dust and will be donated to charity.

column6: Born Loreza
column13: I like these boots soo much
column14: I like these boots soo much.  I tried them on in a store and they *looked* snug around the ankle and calf, which I loved.  Then, I didn't buy them and Born stopped making them.  I searched high and low online to find these boots and sent messages trying to find out what the size was that would best fit me.  I received a half-assed response that did not answer my question and I went ahead and bought a pair much larger than I thought would fit, because It's better to end up with boots too big than too small.  Well, if I wear winter socks, my foot fits in the footbed just great.  Normally I wear a 8.5/9 womens US size, or 39.5 EUR size.  I bought these in a 41.5 and there's no way I could have fit smaller than a 40.5 for these.  I'm okay with how loose they are, but I'm really bummed that they don't hugh my ankle and calf tightly like the size I tried on in the store.  I wear them a lot, but I would wear them more if they fit better.  Zero arch support (does that exist in a heeled shoe anyway?  However, they ARE Born brand shoes, which are one of the only brands of shoes that fit my feet comfortably.  These are the first heeled boots I've bought in a decade, and they do look great.  Too bad they've stopped making them.

I honestly don't know if it's going to get better at this point, it may be the make of the sneaker. My left heel is still being rubbed raw. I have had no name brand sneakers that were way more comfortable.

column14: I originally purchased the croc really sexi flip flop because I was looking for a shower shoe to take to the hospital with me when I delivered my second child. I thought this would be a great shoe for that not only because of its rubber construction (which would prevent the absorption of water) but also because of the simple design and neutral color. I figured this was one shoe that I could continue to use after I got home with no issues. Not only is this flip flop true to size (I generally wear a 7.5 or 8 depending on the shoe and the size 8 fit great) but it is also very comfortable. And it's been a very versatile shoe just like I anticipated it being. I wore this shoe in the hospital shower (my original plan), to walk around my hospital room and I continued to wear it once I got home. They've even been my go to flip flop for beach/pool time. And it's now been over a year since I purchased these and they look no worse for wear. They have proven to be incredibly durable and resilient! All in all, this has got to be the best flip flop that I've ever purchased. No regrets here.

column14: I actually returned these because of the sole material but they are a very nice shoe otherwise.  I've never owned a pair of crocs before so maybe this is a "thing" with their shoes but the cushioning for your feet in these shoes is a rubber/plastic sole with hundreds of little nubs sticking up throughout the sole.  You can barely see them in the photos of the shoes.  I have no idea what this is for, do you really need traction on the sole of your shoe?  All it did for me was make the shoe incredibly uncomfortable.  The sole would maybe work on other shoes but these are just canvas shoes you're going to wear with no socks when you want total comfort, and the soles of these shoes did not provide that for me.  I understand the use of rubber as I have other similar shoes that have similar soles (without the nubs) and they work well to not trap sweat, help when your feet are wet, etc. but the roughness of the crocs soles are something that's just not needed whatsoever on a shoe like this.  If they would fix this issue I think the shoe would be a great product.

column14: Okay, short version is that I LOVED these shoes! If you are even slightly on the fence about these shoes take the plunge they are completely worth it. These are adorable on and the bling gave them just enough for me to be able to dress them up just as much as I wanted to dress them down. I had no problems with any stones coming out and believe me I put these shoes to work. The thing I was not expecting was how comfortable they were. If you have ever been to Vegas before then you know how difficult it is just walking through the hotels, but nothing compared to the strip. I actually walked the strip in these shoes quite a bit during my 6 day trip and wore them in the airport there and back home. Surprisly almost no foot pain! Of course they aren't going to be like walking on clouds but for flat sandals that are actually cute they did a phenomenal job! I'm so glad that I found these shoes now I can strut my stuff in cute shoes and without having to bandage my feet without recognition afterward!

column14: I was so hesitant to buy this wallet after reading reviews about the zipper breaking (reviews read on Fossil's website, not Amazon's), that I called Amazon and nearly cancelled the order.  Amazon's customer service is so great that the representative and I decided together that I would keep the order intact, try the wallet when it arrived, and if the zipper seemed at all flimsy, cheap, breakable, or if I had any doubts, I could return the wallet right away.  She expedited my order at no charge, and set up a follow up call to see how the wallet worked.  Well, I am glad I took the chance.  This is a beautiful wallet and I have not had any zipper problems at all.  It fits everything as advertised.  It has plenty of room.  I've had the wallet for about 3 weeks now, so fingers crossed.  But so far, I could not be happier.  It is the best wallet I have ever had.  Should things go wrong, I will update this review.

Within 20 days of arrival, walking maybe 6-7 thousand steps per day, these shoes have completely broken down- the right shoe sole has split down the middle; the left shoe's vamp has become detached from the sole at the toe. I compared them to my girlfriend's Danskos which she's had for four years (and are actually the same bordeaux color, just to highlight how hilarious the difference is), and hers look like they're in perfect working condition next to my 20-day old Sanitas. Pass over these shoes and get something that lasts longer for your hundred bucks.
