column6: ASICS Women's GEL-Kayano 21 Running Shoe
column13: Great addition to my running collection!
column14:
I have recently gotten into distance running. My first half marathon was in December 2013; since then, I have run four more, and am currently training for my first marathon this upcoming December. If there is anything I have learned through my experiences training for these races, it is how incredibly important it is to have a good shoe designed for your particular stride. I started my training in neutral shoes, and had terrible shin splints and femoropatellar pain. I went to a reputable running shop and had them analyze my gait; they determined that I am a moderate overpronator and recommended I use stability shoes. I started out with the Saucony Omni, which helped my problems a lot and allowed me to comfortably run my first half marathon. After I had worn these shoes out, I moved on to the Brooks Adrenaline GTS; I like those shoes a lot and currently have two pairs. However, I decided that since the intensity of my training is about to go up significantly, I don't want to rely too much on a single brand/model of shoe. Studies have shown that rotating between different models of shoe during training reduces a runner's risk of injury by 39% (Google "rotating running shoes" and see the first Runner's World article that pops up).

So, I set out to research the different types of stability shoes that are available. Eventually, I settled on the Asics Kayano 21 based on positive customer reviews and the well-known brand name. I normally wear a 7-7.5 in regular shoes, but I wear an 8 in my Brooks Adrenalines, so I chose the size 8 for my Asics Kayanos. Compared to the Brooks, the Asics are a little bit longer in the toe. My first impression when trying them on is that they are also a lot cushier than my Brooks, while still providing good arch support. Although they were long in the toe area, they weren't really very wide; my toes felt a little squished during the initial try-on, but not so much so that it ended up being a problem when I actually ran withthem.

So far I have only run once in these shoes, a 6.2 mile break-in run. It felt even better than I hoped for! My most recent pair of Brooks required several runs to break them in; though they feel great now, those first few runs left me with pretty painful feet, even after just a couple miles. In contrast, the Asics remained comfortable through nearly the whole 6.2 miles; my feet only started to feel "tired" for the last couple of miles, and I have had no issues so far with post-run pain.

I realize that a single run probably is not the best basis to write an entire review, so I will come back in a few weeks and update this post when I've had some more time to train in these babies. But my overall first impression is very positive. I love these shoes; I was nervous about branching out from a model of shoe that I know and love, but in the case of the Asics Kayano I think it was a very good decision. Looking forward to many happy miles with them!

column6: Oakley Frogskins Sunglasses
column13: The Frogskins fit and look great, especially the lenses
column14: I think the reviews highlighting the lightness are really missing the point. If you've ever held a $10 pair of cheap Chinese RayBan knock-offs, these aren't the same. The Frogskins are light, but that's really the point. It's a different kind of plastic from what Wayfarers and other glasses use. The idea that heavy plastic = quality is ridiculous. column6: Eurow Sheepskin Women's Hardsole Scuff Slipper - Sand/White
column14: FYI- Pix show my old beat up sz 9 Ugg Coquette along-side brand new sz 10 Eurow Sheepskin Scuff  :b  For reference, pix show NEW "Sand" Womens sz 10 Eurows next to 2 yrs. old beat-up sz 9 Ugg Coquette.  I was concerned w/ reviews stating the soles were stiff, boardlike, heavy, & clunky... Upon receipt, no more-so than Uggs nor any other Sheepskin slipper  üòÄ  They bend where the foot bends (upper/forefoot, just in front of toes).  Not much flex otherwise- These are meant to protect the foot, & provide unmatched shock absorption with each step. Tons of fluffy sheepskin inside, & they custom conform to each owners foot!  btw- These are plenty sturdy for wearing outdoors, walking down the driveway to get the mail, take out the garbage, walk around the yard, even to run errands in car- Will accommodate a wide foot, & the toe-box is wide, tall, & deep, allowing toes to slide fully down into slippers (without being squished).  Real leather uppers w/ shearling (wool) lining & insole, nice & fluffy / dense / cushy Construction is solid/sturdy, & well-designed (except for size- Too short).    These run wide, but WAY short in length. I wear 9's in Uggs Coquette Slippers, (size 8 Uggs fit me too); Womens 10's in Frye boots & other high quality footwear; Yet, these Eurow Women's 10's were too short- (I would need an 11 in these). Since they don't come in 11's, I gave these sz 10's to my daughter, for her Unversity dorm room. (She wears sz 8 Uggs, sz 9 Frye boots & all other shoes). She LOVES them!  üíñ. (Actually, she prefers Eurow's plush comfort over her Uggs!).  Note: 2 decades' experience has taught us to fully expect the insole wool (footbed only) to rub / wear nearly completely off, nearly immediately. Werp are in a frigid winter climate, & this happens to all Sheepskin slippers over the 1st few weeks of wear.  Replacement insoles (which we buy separately here on Amazon for $6-$10/pair) must be inserted when new; & thereafter replaced annually.  Its a lot easier to do so with these $35-$40  beauties, vs. Uggs overpriced $120 model!  In summary- Comfy, plush, real leather upper & genuine sheepskin lining, with sturdy, lightweight outsoles (neither heavy nor overly stiff).  Clunky?  Yes üëå  Eurows rate among the very best / top quality "Sheepskin" type slippers.  Sand Color is beautiful / pale neutral. In summary, if you are accustomed to Uggs, wear size 9 or less, & want that comfort & quality at 1/3 the price, this is your slipper!  (Just be sure to size UP!).   Need a larger size, other TOP quality slippers?  Here's the scoop (4 brands): Eurow's, Dr. Sheepskins, Lamo's (make sure they're genuine Sheepskin version- Lamo sells "synthetics" too), or Brumby's!

I wear  Hi-Tec boots for lawncare and they last longer than any other boots I've wore. The waterproofing is excellent, I hose them off before taking them off to remove dried on grass and they have never gotten wet on the inside. The Vibram soles are treaded nicely, hold up well and provide great traction on slippery grass slopes. I've tried everything from cheap boots to $160 Danners. None are as light, durable or last as long as Hi-Tecs. They are comfortable to wear all day, good support on the inside, constructed well, they stay together when some boots tend to come apart at the seam and sole. Very nice shoe strings too, long enough to double tie. Hi-Tec boots are very comparable to higher priced hiking boots, just as good if not better. I wear size 10 Nikes and size 10 Hi-Tecs fits the same.

People always comment on Poetic License shoes because they are so different  --  but charmingly so. I noticed that PL was offering several of its shoes for ludicrously low prices  --  but all of them featured a lot of orange.  I don't wear orange.  But I ordered three of the sale shoes because I knew that it didn't matter that I don't wear orange.  I just wear them with outfits that "go with" the shoes. column6: carter's Premier B Closed Toe Athletic Sandal (Toddler/Little Kid)
column14: These are great. My 2 year old has his mamma's wide feet. These are wide enough for his big ole foot to fit in there. The straps help keep it snug at the ankle. We're toilet training so these shoes have been a god send. How you may ask. If you have ever toilet trained you know accidents are the norm and of course the shoes take a drowning. Washing and drying will destroy your shoes life expectancy. If little man comes home from school with his shoes in the accident bag, we just pop these bad boys in the dishwasher and the next morning they're good to go. He can put them on by himself (granted not always on the correct foot but hardly the shoes' fault there). I love the closed toe factor. Sandals are great but a lot of preschools will not allow open toed sandals and in the summer who wants to bother with socks and tennis shoes. These meet his school's safety requirements but allow him the cool airy affect that I want. He has now worn these all summer long. The velcro straps are still going strong. The only reason he won't wear these again next year is that they won't fit. The colours are still as true as when they arrived.

column14: Love these shoes!  These are comfortable right out of the box.  Super light and flexible with nice cushion.  The laces are on the short side, but that's perfect for me since I've always double knotted my other shoes to shorten the laces to prevent tripping on them.  Some shoes are stiff until I break them in, but these are great on the first run.  I have average width feet with narrow heels and moderate arch.  These give me plenty of support and cushion, but I'm only 5 feet and 90 pounds, so I don't have the average need for heavier duty shoes.  I run an average of 3-5 miles daily on paved bike/walking trail and packed sand (at the beach) in Newport Beach, CA.  These are my favorite running shoes so far.

I have played about 10 rounds in these and there was no break-in - they just felt good from the first hole to the last. I don't know if this is all about the "boost" material or not, but after my experience with these I will be trying out some boost running shoes. My suggestion is to try the boost on before you buy anything else. Maybe you will agree with me, maybe not.

column6: Delicious Women Kayla-S pumps-shoes, Black Imsu, Size 7
column14:
Comfort: I wore these shoes all around downtown San Diego and my feet felt wonderful after. I recommend stretching out the shoes in trouble spots around toes and heels before attempting a long night out with them. Great for any event that requires a dress shoe.
Craftsmanship: Lets be real these are not made to last forever, but they are perfect for the price. The faux suede is the best I have seen on this type of shoe, because it actually has some durability. Now I wouldn't take them out in bad weather, but it beats similar shoes where it looks like the manufacturer used a flocked velvet to coat the shoe only to have it rub off in two wears, that was not the case with this.
Fit: I wear a 6.5 normally and was advised in the comments to go up a size. I opted for the 7 and was very pleased with the choice.
Overall its a great little shoe for business, pleasure, or even a dress casual event.

column13: I like them a lot, but oddly my Danskos still combat fatigue and pain better
column14:
Bought these to combat rheumatoid arthritis...my previous ASICS were a GT 4000 (?) series ( a trail running shoe)...good but not as hard-core as these...they are pretty good at combating pain and fatigue all day....larger outside shoe than those as well. So far, though, nothing beats my Dansko shoes that have the sole that is one generation after the standard clog...the one with the cutaway heel and rocker toes. Only shoes that do not cause fatigue from standing a good deal of the day. I don't realize I have foot problems when I wear these.

These are best for movement, still not enough something, not sure what, to eliminate pain/aching from standing and walking at work. They are nice and cushy, but maybe the firmer soles of the Danskos provides the needed support.

column6: KEEN Men's Clearwater CNX Sandal
column13: CNX vs. H2 - I'll take the CNX
column14: I really like how light these sandals are. They feel like wearing nothing compared to my old Newport H2's. I bought the CNX as a replacement for my H2's, which are sadly falling apart after years of service. The CNX are (as the name implies) made for the beach/lake/water more than hiking or trail stuff. The design is much more open with larger spacing between the webs and the webs themselves are thinner. They work fine for everyday stuff around town like errands or shopping. I just got back from a cruise and I had them on all day, every day. The only exception was when I had to wear dress up shoes for dinner, but after that I was back in the room changing into my sandals. When walking on the beach, sand easily comes out the sides and doesn't stack up between my foot and the sole. That was not the case with the H2, which I had to take off and shake out if I got sand or small rocks in them. The reason for only 4 stars is because I am accustom to having the cushion of my old Newport H2 sandals, but that comes with having a lighter and thinner sole. I'm willing to make that trade.

column6: Altra Women's Intuition 2 Running Shoe
column13: Try Altra shoes for natural comfort!
column14: I have ordered Altra shoes directly from them and noticed sizing seemed to run small according to reviews. So I purposely ordered one half size larger.  This style is a new one for me and I do really like the shoes. Altra shoes are wider in the toe box to allow your toes to spread out naturally. If you have bunions, these shoes are great.  Also they I previously wore Kalso Earth Shoes because of the wider toe box but a few years ago, they narrowed their foot bed so can no longer wear them. I am a walker and love these Altra shoes! Altra shoes also have a zero drop heel which means the toe and heel are on the same plane. Kalso Earth Shoes have a negative heel, a lower one than the toe. Both are better than having a higher heel.  They both take some getting used to, if your wear heels alot.  Your achilles tendon (calves) needs to be stretched which takes some adjustment. You wll love these shoes!

column6: OOFOS Unisex OOcloog Clog
column13: Made an excellent gift for Grandpa
column14:
My Grandpa has a habit of wearing his house slippers outside, and in the extremely humid zone where he lives, you can imagine how messed up and nasty fabric slippers get going through dampness all the time. I positively do not like Crocs, and he prefers shoes that are completely open in the back. I found these while searching for leather slippers, and I could not be happier with the product!

He wears about a 9D, and I bought these in a 10 since he needs shoes with good arch support and a fairly wide bridge. These fit those requirements exactly. They're made of a flexible yet thick rubber material, so I have no concerns he'd slip while walking (which is great, because they don't have carpet indoors). He hardly takes them off.

They clean very easily and don't hold mud in the treads, a feature that's not always easy to find in shoes that can handle going outdoors. There's only a little bit of space behind his heels, which is a good thing if you plan to give them to someone who has issues with foot swelling. They look exactly as pictured. I'm seriously considering a pair for myself.

Overall, they'd make a great gift for anyone and are worth the money. Highly recommended!

column6: Shoe Horn Pro Precision - Premium Extra Long Handled Telescopic, Twist & Lock To 24‚Äù & 30‚Äù, Extendable Collapsible, Stainless Steel (Black)
column13: Product technically works, but I think there are cheaper/better options from less irritating companies.
column14:
Okay, let me be honest for a minute and admit that I had I not found this sellers incessant SPAM-LIKE emailing about "customer service" and "please give negative feedback directly to us" annoying and a little sketchy, I would probably not have reviewed this product at all.

However, since it's now obvious they are trying to stop people from giving their product negative reviews (which irks me because honest costumer reviews are one of the best things about amazon) I know feel obligated to review this product in full detail.

The product arrived on time and as described and if you follow the instruction the item does "work." However, I think they have gone and made what was a simple effective tool more complicated than it needed to be, and now it doesn't work as well as just a basic traditional shoe horn.

The fact that the shoe horn bends MAY make it more comfortable and be better for your shoes, but it makes it a WAY LESS effective shoe horn. Technically it does still allow me to get the shoe on my foot, but with so much effort that the shoe horn hardly saves me anytime from just slowly forcing the shoe on myself.

Knowing what I know now I would buy the cheapest "4 star" shoe horn on the market and only waste my time dealing with this e-mail spamming, time wasting company if I had REALLY EXPENSIVE shoes that I was worried would get damaged by a traditional shoe horn.

column6: Toms Unisex-Adult Charlie Rae Sunglasses
column14: I love these glasses. They are stylish and functional. But I need to say something here. For glasses that are just shy of $200, I would expect a little more. They are not built very well. First of all, the glasses start to loosen up as you wear them more so they start to slide down your face because there is no nose pad in the bridge. I liked this aspect at first since often times my hair would get caught in the nose pads.  But now seeing that I need to take the glasses to a Tom's shop for them to heat the and adjust them is just annoying. Also, one of the screws came lose and so one of the lenses popped out. I was doing something pretty active just to be fair but it seemed fixable. I went in with a tiny screw driver and I because the screw is made from softer metal, it was stripped. Now that's pretty cheap considering these glasses are NOT cheap. Overall, I'm not happy. My glasses tend to last me a few years as I take good care of a purchase like this. I bought these glasses 6 months ago and I feel like they are on their last legs. Not ok.

column6: Crocs Women's Beach Line Boat Shoe
column14:
I'm sorry, but these shoes are ugly, so I returned them. There are too many cute shoes in the world that are also comfortable to wear these. As for the people who claim that they are good to work in, I would never wear something w/ as thin a sole as these & expect them to support my feet all day. Good supportive shoes need a thicker, bouncier sole & adequate arch support.
Then there is the narrow, skimpy profile that tries to pull off a boat shoe look, but just looks cheap & fails... The plastic looks cheap when we all know that Crocs can be expensive, so there's no need for the unflattering matte brown finish & the appearance of a shoe design that was thrown together @ the last minute. Even Payless sells nicer looking shoes! This shoe's one redeeming quality is that it easily fits a wider foot-- have to at least give them that.

To be fair, the pink & blue version of this shoe was probably a more fashion forward look, but I was not going to shell out more money for a summer shoe in a color combination that I was never going to wear. I guess that I'm not this brand's target customer cuz I think shoes should look nice AND be comfortable.

column14: I got these to garden in. I like to be able to feel the ground beneath my feet, and historically I would go out into the garden barefoot for that reason. However, getting holly leaves incessantly stuck in my feet led to a great feeling of "enough is enough." I have somewhat wide feet for their size, and I have difficulty finding shoes that are wide enough, so I was worried that these would also be too narrow. And technically, they are, my feet spill over the sides of the soles. The canvas is flexible though so I can still force my feet in to them and buckle them up. Over a couple wears, they more or less had stretched to conform to the shape of my feet and are quite comfortable. The breathability isn't fantastic, but I also can't imagine why anyone would wear them for an entire day to begin with. For my purposes, they are perfect, and don't even look that ridiculous until you really scrutinize them. When these wear out, I will likey get another pair.

column13: Decent and reasonably priced running shoe
column14:
I do wish I would have tried on a pair before I ordered them. Because I would have ordered up a size or a half. So they seem to run a little smaller than other brands. Still, after breaking them in, and wearing thinner socks, I haven't had any problems with them. They are a pretty no frills running shoe though. For the $40 I paid for them, I can't complain too much.

The size issue is mostly just related to ordering footwear online when uniform sizings are more of an industry suggestion than a hard rule. So as a running shoe goes, it does it's job, and it's cheap enough to take a chance on. Just think about ordering bigger than what you might normally wear, or go try on a couple pairs first.

column14:

These glasses hit the ground at 60+mph, onto pavement, and you can hardly tell. There a few nicks that you can see if you looking for them, but other than that they are 100 percent fine.

I am completely blown away. I don't see myself ever buying a pair of glasses other than Ray-Bans from here on out.

column6: Salomon Men's Speedcross 3 Trail Running Shoe
column14: I purchased these shoes in camo for an upcoming archery elk hunt. Last year I used the Nike Special Field Boot, which are pretty nice, but my feet were killing me after only a day or two in crazy steep terrain. Both big toes were numb for 3 months afterward. It was time for a change. The Salomon Speedcross 3 are super-comfy right out of the box. They fit snug and have a soft feel to them. The traction feels extremely grippy. I've only been using them on morning runs as hunting season begins in a few weeks. I really like the way these shoes feel so far. The true test will be getting them up in the mountains. I wear size 11 and ordered a half-size up to help keep my toes from slamming into the front toe box. I was worried than size 11.5 would look like clown shoes on me, but they feel perfect on my feet and still have a bit of room up front for the steep terrain. The lacing system is fast and efficient. Can't wait to use them in the field.

column6: Woodlore Mens' Ultra Shoe Tree
column13: GREAT...BUT I USE THEM TO STRETCH BOOTS, WHICH THEY ARE XLNT FOR
column14:
these are amazing, and would probably be the best shoe trees you could get. HOWever, i use them for an even more demanding purpose.

i actually get these 2 sizes up and use to stretch out my cowboy western boots that may be a bit tight lengthwise or need more room in the toe.

they have a true natural foot shape that is a great match to the last they use on making shoes and boots, that if your shoe/boot is slightly tight or slightly lacking in length, this can make the difference. note, it will NOT increase your boots a full size, or even a half size...but you may be able to get 1/4 of a size added in length and toe width, which could make all the difference.

not that i purposely get shoes small, but when it comes to cowboy boots, i am between an 11 and a 10.5 D...and rather than get the oversize, i get the 10.5 and am able to stretch the leather (yes, the hard front toe portion will expand slightly with some effort). the normal size as a 'boot tree' in these would be a Large, so i go up to XXLarge (two sizes up) and the spring is completely contracted, and i use some effort to stuff these into the shoes, and leave them that way until there is some expansion. i'd say you can get 1/4 of a size increase in length, and up to 1/2 size in toe width, or something like a D to an EE.

it helps if you use these with a toe stretcher (the aluminum are expensive but work best), and also break them in with some good walking.

that these are truly amazing to help you get that extra expansion/stretch that will turn a very uncomfortable pair of boots/shoes into a winner. this is an extreme use for these, and you may wish to try getting them only 1 oversize, rather than the 2 that i do...but these work so well as stretchers that it is clear that simple use as a shoe tree (correct size use) these would also be the best.

column6: Tommy Hilfiger Women's Edessa Dress Sandal
column14:
Okay, really pretty shoes, look great on, about as comfortable as one would expect from 5" platforms for the first few weeks. But I've had them a few weeks now, worn a couple days a week, and I noticed that they were hurting a bit more than the normal excessively tall heels.

So I checked them out, and, right under the pad of the big toe there's this worn spot in the leather insole about the size of screw head (center of picture). And under that, is what I can only describe as a horribly placed screw head, sticking up about 1/8" above the surrounding cork insole. The padded cork insole is held down with a metal screw, and, shockingly, after a little wear, the padded cork insole is not as resilient as the METAL SCREW.

Yes, ladies and gentlemen who are into women's shoes, METAL IS HARDER THAN PADDING.

I mean, I really like these shoes, except the horrible pain of walking on screws.

I have worn these twice so far. One 30 mile ride and one 50 mile ride. The shoes are slightly narrow for my foot, but I could not find anywhere online selling the maxi version in my size and I really liked the shoes. My right foot is slightly wider and was slightly cramped after my first ride, but the shoes have stretched a bit and my foot was fine for my second longer ride. I ordered a few different brands and liked the way the mavics fit the best. Plus in the price range, felt they were constructed really well and of good materials compared to some other brands.

I'm using these for road biking and prefer the SPD style cleat over the SPD SL cleat due to being able to walk easier and also not needing to replace your cleats due to them being metal and recessed.

column14:
I have purchased this case in the hope that it will serve me better than the string of \\\snap-shut\\\\\" spectacle cases on which the spring has failed (so killing the \\\\\"snap-shut\\\\\" and leaving my specs to fall out). column6: Baggallini Horizon Crossbody
column14: I just returned from a trip to London where I used a bag similar to this.  While I love Baggallini bags for their light weight and organization capabilities, there was one feature that I found to be a drawback.  Since the weather was warm, I did not need to wear a jacket and wore the bag cross-body over lightweight tee shirts.  The canvas strap has very rough edges, and as I walked (many miles), the strap literally sawed a sore spot on my neck.  While the strap is definitely sturdy, which is an advantage on crowded subways and buses, I don't think I would carry this bag again unless it is over a jacket or coat with a collar between the strap and my skin.  I notice that some other Baggallini bags have the strap made of the same nylon as the bag - I think if I buy another I will definitely look for one with a strap like that instead of the heavy nylon canvas.

column13: Exclusively wore these, but the quality's decreased.  Time to find a new shoe!
column14:
I have worn these shoes exclusively for the last 8 years or so.

Recently, though, they've changed in quality. With my newest pair, my feet hurt after just a small amount of walking. I find my knees also sort of point in a bit, and everything is out of alignment (feet bones, ankles, knees, hips, back). My toes and the balls of my feet are in pain after even small amounts of walking. In my hiking boots, I don't have these problems.

Prior pairs, before the drop in quality, have lasted me at least a year without degradation in support (at least, it's not noticeable until I get a new pair, but it never outright hurt to wear them).

Time to find a new shoe!

column6: NIKE Golf Men's NIKE FI Impact Golf Shoe, Med Base Grey/Team Orange//Black, 11.5 D(M) US
column13: Incredible comfort... but make sure they're for you.
column14:
These are incredibly light and comfortable. Note that the bottom is a softer material which is great for comfort but it won't hold up as well. I walk a few rounds a week and these are some of the most comfortable shoes I've worn on the course. However, after two weeks, I noticed small sticks were sticking into the bottom material and leaving small holes when i pulled them out.

Just be aware that any shoe with a softer sole material will allow the most comfort but you will sacrifice some durability. That's just physics and not any bearing on the quality of the product. That's why I'm giving these five stars. They are amazing golf shoes and perfect for a day on the course. If you stay on the fairway and cart path you should be fine but if you're like me and like to adventure out and about during a round then these (and other soft-soled shoes) may not be the best option for you.

I enjoy looking for lost golf balls... I find 100 or so balls a month and use them to hit around the yard at home. It's like an easter egg hunt every time I play:)

column14:
I needed to replace my old sunglasses and wanted something that looked similar, and that were polarized. These seemed to fit the bill and the reviews were all very positive, although many of them seemed to be "paid for" by the manufacturer looking to build up a good image. Here is my review:

Cons: While I did see that the shipping was a bit longer than usual, I didnt expect it to take 11 business days (15 days total). I ordered on July 24th, and got them on August 7th. I contacted the manufacturer, got a prompt response, and they indicated that the glasses were shipping from China. It seems that these are now available on Prime, so this may no longer be an issue. Also, they don't fit into regular sized sunglasses cases. When the legs are folded, the depth of the glasses are still quite large. You may be able to squeeze them in, but then you are starting to bend the frames a little and I didn't want to do this.

Neutral: They come with a little plastic card begging for good feedback. I guess I can understand why the manufacturer does this, but shouldn't they let the product speak for itself? Almost seems to be "begging", but then again, it worked. Here I am giving feedback!

Pros: the glasses come packed in a sturdy Styrofoam "casket" that ensured these glasses (I got 2) didnt budge. They come with a soft pouch to keep them in, as well as a small little cleaning cloth. They fit very well on my head and look great. I have already gotten several compliments. They are polarized, which is a must (I have gotten other glasses that claim to be polarized and arent) and they are perfect for driving, boating, and running (I used them for all 3 purposes this weekend).

Summary: I am normally not a patient person when I order things online. I want it tomorrow, usually because if I order something I need it ASAP. With that said, these were worth the wait.

column13: Well Made and Ready For Action
column14:
I put no for good arch support because the sole of the shoe is basically not there. If you're flat footed, then I probably wouldn't recommend these shoes for you. But if you have a nice arch on your foot, then they perform perfectly. I just got them today so don't trust my review 100%, but I bought a different shoe a while ago. The Take Flight 1.0 and those shoes had less padding than these. I can drop from 7 feet and land well. (Don't try that. You could get yourself hurt unless you're a trained professional) They fit snug if you know your shoe size well. I don't expect my feet to grow much more since they are already 12's (I picked a size 11.5 and it was bigger than I expected, but once I tied them to my feet, they were snug), So I would pick either a shoe size 1/2 smaller (Like from 12, and subtract 0.5), or get whatever your shoe size is. This shoe is amazing for parkour, I can say that, and a great running shoe all around. The bottom of the shoe DOES have grip. Some people are just training on the slippery surfaces. It works very well with concrete, and wood, but metal surfaces can be a bit slippery if it's the wrong kind of metal.
5 stars, great shoe, running shoe, Parkour shoe
It's a really nice shoe. If you want it, buy it!

column6: Cordani Women's Darnell Wedge Sandal
column14:
Hmmm, I walk a LOT (my FitBit makes me do it!) but I like to look cute while doing so, if I'm walking to/from/during work. So I'm always looking for comfortable, attractive shoes that I can walk at least a few miles in without pain.

I will say that these shoes are 95% comfortable. There's just this one little inner-bump on the side strap of ONE shoe that digs into the side of my foot like nobody's business.It literally created a scab, even with a band-aid.

It's possible that the shoes are just a tad too small - I'm between a 7.5 and an 8, and ordered my 'usual', the 38. If the shoe were any shorter, my toes would hang off the front. I think that in the absence of that one area noted above, these shoes would be fantastic - and really, I think this little 'flaw' is just unique to me and my foot (my feet are not well padded. . .) so this might work for others just fine.

Would I buy them again? Probably not. But ultimately, I'm keeping the shoes because I've worn them several times and they're really not returnable at this point - I'm going to see about getting some moleskin to put on the offending strap, though, so I can wear them more frequently and for longer stretches of time.

column6: Teva Women's Zirra Sandal
column14: These are super cute. I really like them, but they are very flexible and not too supportive.  UPDATE: I have had these just over a year now, and they have become my favorite sandals. the fact that they are softer than the athletic sandals than I'm used to worked to my advantage. When I first got them, the arch of my foot didn't feel supportive like the other sandals and shoes I had for plantar fasciitis, and I didn't think they would work for me. Turns out, that contrary to what my doctors thought, the lack of arch was exactly what my feet needed to feel better. I have even upgraded to minimalist in my everyday shoe, because of these sandals, and my feet are doing better than they have in years. The only downfall I have found with these is that my feet sometimes go a little crooked wth the strap set up.

column6: adidas Performance Men's Response Boost Techfit M Running Shoe
column13: Outstanding for workouts on hard surfaces requiring jumping, great for people with odd toes. :)
column14:
I have weird feet. The kind prone to taylor's bunions, also sporting a bad case of plantar fasciitis.

Unfortunately for me, shoe manufacturers nor workout studios don't give a damn. For the former, nearly every shoe I should be using is too narrow. On the latter, concrete/wooden floors are evil. Even more so when they involve jumping jacks, burpees, mountain climbers, pushups, and/or other exercises when pounding is inevitable.

These shoes are awesome; the boost thing no joke. That little extra padding goes a very long way in transferring impact on landing. Also, I absolutely adore the stretchy mesh surface that gives my funky small toes a needed break.

If you're color agnostic, these bad boys can be had for ~$40. Buy two pairs, amigos.

I bought the Boost 2.0 for the better half (complaining of knee problems,)...and knee pain no more.

column14:

I like the climbing style lacing as I was able to dial in the fit for a hike that required lots of time on my toes. Coming down, the traction was a savior on loose rock!

I rarely review products, but I highly recommend this boot!

column6: ALTEC VISION Vintage Retro Classic Half Frame Horn Rimmed Sunglasses with Polycarbonate Lenses - Choose Your Color
column14:
These sunglasses come in a high quality cloth bag that feels similar to that of Oakley's.
The polarized mirror lenses come with a dark amber tint, which look great in full sun environments.
The lenses scratches really easily. I've had them for a couple of days and only cleaned a smudge off of them with the cloth bag and I already have a few light scratches.
The lenses also appear to be a little loose in the frame as it can squeak and move a little during cleaning.

Conclusion: these are one of the best low cost sunglasses that you can buy. The lenses could be a lighter to use in more lighting situations.

Pros: polarized mirror lenses, frames are nicely built with metal hinges, low cost, good fit, nice cloth bag.
Cons: lenses scratch easily and can be a better fit for the frame.

column14: Beware of the amt in the bottle. NOT 12 oz, maybe not even the 10.5 oz it says ON the bottle. I've used my old pack many times this summer. The dirt just brushes right off and as many times as I've been rained on, the stuff in my pack stays dry. So in spite of the missing 1.5 oz this stuff still gets a solid 5 stars from me. I do wish the seller would change the ad for this product. They are making themselves look bad. Please note-this stuff might work too good sometimes. It water proofed my bivy tent so good that I woke up with a damp interior from the condensation of my breathing! column14:
Someone in the comments had suggested that if you wear a half size, to order the next size up. This didn't work for me. I wear a 9.5 and ordered a 10, and they are FAR too big. I don't blame Joy Fish for this poor information.

To boots themselves are good quality, but the return policy stinks. On top of paying for return postage, they require a $12 check to be included in the box. I'm used to Amazon's generous return policy on clothing. I realize that this is not sold directly from Amazon, but it makes no sense to pay shipping twice (once to get to me, once to get back to them), plus $12. It's not worth my time or energy to box up the boots and send them back for what will end up being a dollar or two refunded.

LUCKILY this is for a Halloween costume so I don't have to wear them long. If I double up my socks and pad the toes I can hobble around enough to make this work.

column6: DREAM PAIR SIMPLE-L/FLIPPA New Women's Casual Solid Crochet Comfort Lady Flats Loafers
column13: Pokey and stiff but fixable. Pretty cute!
column14: The biggest issue was that they were pokey. The form of the shoe is made with nylon fiber (like a tight mesh made out of fishing line or fiber optics) with the pretty lace sewn to that on top. Looks great! But in some spots where the nylon mesh was cut, it poked through the fabric into my skin and was very uncomfortable and irritating. I went along the inside of the shoe and with nail clippers trimmed the pokey spots then filed them down with a nail file. I'm pretty sure that resolved the issue for now anyway but I'm not sure if it will last and took me 30 minutes to fix (not to bad really). They came smaller than I expected but totally my fault. I wear 8 1/2 in heels and I always forget to go up a half size for my flats, maybe that's just me. But I can definitely still wear them. They were very stiff so I had to bend them a bunch to get them to feel a bit more comfortable. After all of the work I think I really like them. They will be my emergency shoes at my friends wedding next week when my heels start to destroy my life!

Admittedly, I have a wide head but not so wide that I'm unable to buy reading glasses off the rack at the drug store. column14: Bought same boots 6 or 7 years ago for central florida yard work - chores.  Had good experience with them.  They are not gore-tex lined.  The leather and a decent soft insole is all you get.  Mine are not steel toe.  Sometimes completely soaked through working on sprinklers, florida rains, etc.  No lining allows them to dry out pretty well over night.  Shovel digging eventually chunked up the soles on my first pair...but they were old by then.  They are not vibram hard rubber soles.  I got more than my money's worth from them.  Just purchased my second pair.  Identical to first.  Soft leather, like well-oiled ball glove...soft soles (not vibram durability though)...comfort right away.  There is exposed stitching inside that could cause blisters for some shapes of feet, but I'm lucky I guess.  I use a thin insole insert on top of the original insole...I don't have big feet...size 8.  I don't need to do this...the size is correct.  It just makes the fit more like a running shoe.  It works for me.  Box says Dominican Republic.  Kind of a different look than most boots.  I've also had wolverines, montrail, other brands, some Gore-Tex, some vibram soles.  Boots are tools.

column13: Comfort and style at a great price
column14: The comfort of a Croc with a look elegant enough for work. I am a teacher, so I am constantly on my feet. After buying eventually shelving many pairs of shoes from multiple companies, I stumbled upon these shoes in a local shoe store. Desperate for relief from daily foot, leg, and back pain, I purchased a pair. The first thing one immediately notices when wearing these shoes is the amount of support and comfort they provide. The soft foam is thick and rigid enough for comfortably walking over gravel pathways, yet soft and springy enough for all day wear. Another feature that I really love about these, is the width. I have a somewhat wide foot, and I have often had trouble with shoes being just narrow enough to rub and cause blisters. Not so with these shoes. They manage to be wide enough without looking masculine. Another thing that I love, is the affordable price of these sandals. I now own five pairs of Croc's Meleens like this, in multiple colors, and I love every pair. Having a great combination of style and comfort, I recommend these shoes for home and work!

column6: Powerstep Pinnacle Plus Full Length Orthotic Shoe Inserts - Built-In Metatarsal Support
column13: Helps with ball of foot pain
column14: I have an injury to the sesamoid bone which is in the ball of the foot.  The power step insoles tend to work well for me in general, But this one with the extra cushioning for the metatarsal, is the best match for off loading pressure on the ball of the foot.  Before I got this Insole, I was using dancer pads to help compensate.  Dancer pads do help, but adding that with an insole created so much bulk all my shoes were too tight.  Finding this Insole allows the same improvement when walking without having to use the dancer pad.  They fit perfectly into my shoe.  I'm using the women's 7-7.5 to fit a 6.5 wide shoe size.  This puts the arch support right where I need it, and I have not had to trim the insole.

column6: Five Ten Men's Guide Tennie Leather Approach Shoe
column14: Great approach/hiking shoe. These things are super comfortable and have no problem taking abuse.  I broke them in at work for a couple weeks before there first outing.  Climbed Giant Mtn. in the Adirondacks via the ridge trail for a quick 6 miles to see how they handled rocky/wet trails and some low angle slab. Unreal. Grip is outstanding and they are very comfortable.  Then it was time to test how they would do on a long day of climbing.  Started with Saddleback's newish (Irene) slide "Back in the saddle" then went down the cliffs over to Basin, up and over Little Hay to Haystack and back out the phelps to the southside trail to the rt. 73 (garden was full...) total mileage for the day ended up being just shy of 27 miles. The confidence in having traction on the steep slabs and scrambles makes a huge difference.  Also very helpful on quick descents, hopping from wet rock to wet rock down streambeds. I will be buying another pair to have on hand and my wife also has a pair and loves them.

column13: Comfort and style at a great price
column14: The comfort of a Croc with a look elegant enough for work. I am a teacher, so I am constantly on my feet. After buying eventually shelving many pairs of shoes from multiple companies, I stumbled upon these shoes in a local shoe store. Desperate for relief from daily foot, leg, and back pain, I purchased a pair. The first thing one immediately notices when wearing these shoes is the amount of support and comfort they provide. The soft foam is thick and rigid enough for comfortably walking over gravel pathways, yet soft and springy enough for all day wear. Another feature that I really love about these, is the width. I have a somewhat wide foot, and I have often had trouble with shoes being just narrow enough to rub and cause blisters. Not so with these shoes. They manage to be wide enough without looking masculine. Another thing that I love, is the affordable price of these sandals. I now own five pairs of Croc's Meleens like this, in multiple colors, and I love every pair. Having a great combination of style and comfort, I recommend these shoes for home and work!

column6: Dragon Age Inquisition
column13: Great Game, Just not as a Dragon Age game
column14:
I will start of by saying that I would give the game a 3.5 overall if I could but a flat 3 is just too low, so 4 it is.

STORY: As a standalone franchise, Inquisition probably could have been a good story. As a Dragon Age game, it just wasn't there. The way Bioware tried to link it back to Origins was just weak in my opinion. The inclusion of characters from Origins could have completely been avoided and felt a bit gratuitous. I feel like they really dropped the ball on trying to tie it back to the previous games. And the big "Plot Twist" during the epilogue just felt completely disjointed. As I said, were it a standalone game, it could have been much much better. But as a DA game, I just didn't feel like it fit. 3 Stars

GAME PLAY: The game play is ok. I feel as if the analogy of one step forward, two steps back applies here. Bioware removed a couple of features that were integral to the other DA games. The first of which is the ability to use magic to heal your party. Yes, you read that right, a mage can no longer heal your party. You rely solely on potions and can carry a limited amount of them. Secondly, you can no longer set character actions. In Origins you were able to say "If X happens, do Y". You can no longer do this in Inquisition. Your choices are reduced to "Follow" or "Protect" the main character. You can set attacks and actions as "favorites" but it is nowhere near as expansive as being able to tell your mage "when I'm at 20% health, heal me" or telling your tank "Attack the enemy with the highest health". The removal of this feature was very disappointing to me as it felt like an integral part of the previous games. I suppose the inclusion of the "touch-pad combat" was intended to mitigate that but I never got used to it. In fact I played and beat the entire game using that feature twice; and it wasn't missed. And the side quests; oy, talk about monotonous. No variety here whatsoever. Very long in the tooth. 2.5 Stars

GRAPHICS: This is where the game really excels! The graphics are beautiful! The level design is outstanding and the variety of levels is wonderful. From the desert levels to the completely forested, to the sea side, each one was done beautifully. Character and enemy design were great. And the Dragons.....well done! 5 Stars

SOUNDTRACK: Again, one of the places the game excels. The soundtrack is wonderful and reminds me of something you would hear in an Elder Scrolls game. 5 Stars

REPLAY: I will probably replay the game at some point as a different class but not any time soon. 2.5 Starstonous. No variety here whatsoever. Very long in the tooth. 2.5 Stars

column6: inFAMOUS Second Son - PlayStation 4
column14:
I am an avid fan of the inFamous series and I can say that this game is by far my favorite!

STORY: The story in this game is as fresh to the series as it is engaging. I was afraid of what they were going to do with it as I felt inFamous 2 was a bit lackluster. The fact that they use a real city (Seattle) as the setting was wonderful. Sometimes introducing new characters into a series is a big risk but Sucker Punch pulled it off beautifully with Second Son. There are plenty of twists and turns to keep you engaged and not feel like you are rehashing the story of the first two. 5 Stars

GAMEPLAY: I was very refreshing to have a variety of powers not seen in the other two installments. The controls never felt clunky and you always feel like you have total control of Delsin. The one draw back is the collectibles and side quests. As with most sandbox games, these get a bit tedious and can become a bit of a grind. 4.5 Stars

VOICE ACTING: Incredible! Like some other reviewers, I immediately missed Cole. But as the story progressed, you could definitely feel the emotion and each actor fit the game character perfectly. 5 Stars

GRAPHICS: Very good! The game design and character modelling was done wonderfully. Advertised as a "next gen" game on release....certainly doesn't disappoint. 5 Stars

SOUNDTRACK: Loved the music to this game. It was very different from anything I had heard previously and it fit the game wonderfully. 5 Stars

REPLAY: Played it back to back. Massive replay-ability as it maintains the "good" and "evil" plot lines. 5 Stars

As I stated above, this game exceeded every expectation I had for it.

column6: PDP Afterglow PS4 Bluetooth Communicator
column13: It does what it says, and Yes it is for the PS4
column14:
For those interested I have decided to put my thoughts down regarding the PDP afterglow as there are many bad reviews out there and frankly I feel it is necessary to shed some light on this product.
First let me start by saying that the product is very easy to use and incredibly versatile, although it does suffer from a few issues, which is why I gave it only 4 stars rather than 5.
The first notable issue may be with the specific model I purchased.
The afterglow is designed with a UNIVERSAL (more on that later) U.S.B. Bluetooth dongle which auto pairs when plugged in.
The included headset is easy to set up, and fairly well made, although I found its sound quality to be less than stellar. I attribute this to an issue with lack of shielding from the headset to the mic itself which renders some echo and static.
With testing across multiple headsets I found the best sound quality generated from a Plantronics model M50 headset, (voyager 320,340, and "generic" were also tested.)
The dongles performance is decent with roughly a 30-40 ft. range as standard with Bluetooth, and with degrading quality from there.

I found with a bit of experimentation that I could design a holder using an extension to change the angle of the dongle to upright, which is more fitting for this style transmission, and achieved ranges something in the tune to the upper 30's.

When auto pairing does not find a device it continually tries and sends the PS4 into a loop of "mic connected disconnected."
The simple solution to this would have been a hardware force to pair button, and I believe another model has this function, although I have yet to contact the manufacturer to see if an exchange is viable. Regardless this is the model I am reviewing, so it's an issue for me as I must unplug the dongle between uses which is a bit bothersome. A simple workaround I have eventually planned is to design a long cable extension to go on topof my entertainments center with a simple switch to turn off between uses. I am aware that not everyone is able to do this, but with elevation, vertical placement and possibly a slight signal amp I think I can get transmission ranges to the tune of the upper 40 foot range.

So lets get to a bit of a summary for this regarding cons:
Constantly polls giving the PS4 multiple personality disorder
Stock headset is metallic sounding with tinny echo and poor range.
Suffers from a classic issue with radio placement in which the overall range would be far better if upright. (although easily fixed.

As far as the Pros go:
It's just about fully universal (I have not yet tested with stereo units, but that's around the corner.)
Works really well with certain model headsets. (just not the one it comes with)
You can untether yourself from your controller without shelling out $100 for inferior usb. (Thanks for the cash grab Sony)
You can pour a cup of coffee while chatting without risking your controller (see above)
While using, as your sound is now isolated, controller battery times go back to typical ps3 controller times as the unit is not driving speakers.
It is fairly reliable and pairing is incredibly simple (although I would have liked a momentary switch or even a "pairing mode" function)
It does what no other current device does, effectively allowing you to use a simple headset, run your sound through your stereo without being forced to a single headset brand. (This is the big one which sold me!)

column6: Final Fantasy XII
column14:
In my opinion this is, thus far, the best final fantasy. There are side quests. There a lot of optional areas, a lot of optional espers, and in the midst of all of this a very compelling storyline. Each character has his or her important part to play. No one seems like a 'token' and you see growth in perhaps all of them except for Fran [who keeps to herself].
The romance is subtle--Ash wants revenge for her lost love and Balthier and Fran keep it professional but are clearly together.
Great voice actors, and the world is ENORMOUS. You won't get bored.
I think what people do not like about this game is the gambit system. I personally like being able to go into an area and not have to button mash. Also, because the enemies can be very, very fast, without your gambits set up well, it can be the end. That is, unless you adjust the battle speed.
I wish that the license board was a tad bit bigger.
And I wish Fran's stats weren't so deplorably low.

column6: Hydra Performance DS Lite Rechargeable Battery for DSlite 3.7V 1800mAh
column13: So bad I'm not even going to demand a refund
column14:
I'm so disgusted by this piece of garbage that I'm not even going to bother asking Amazon for a refund. I'm going to chalk it up as another lesson about why I should never buy non-OEM parts in certain situations.

This battery charged in two hours or less (I walked away after plugging it in, my DS Lite wouldn't even power on with the original battery in it after sitting in a drawer for a couple of years). When I pulled the cord and started playing Puzzle Quest Galactrix (weird obsession, don't judge!), the battery only lasted 9 minutes.

I thought maybe it's just a quirk of a new battery and all, so plugged it back in and walked away once I saw it was charging. I remember getting many hours of use out of the DS Lite when we were using it regularly, so after it was charged with the new battery again, I unplugged and continued my game. 9 minutes later, the red light is blinking and then it powered down.

Fast forward to six days of this, just because I'm like that and need to make sure I'm not crazy. This battery holds just at 9 minutes of charge before flatlining. About fifteen minutes ago I ordered a proper OEM replacement battery direct from Nintendo. $15 + $5 shipping, which is about 3x as much as this battery, but I feel much, much better about life now.

In short: do not buy this. Some have had decent results. Most seem to be in my boat. Just spend the extra money for the proper part unless you dig gambling.

column6: Xbox One Wireless Controller [Without Bluetooth]
column13: Good controller with flawed new functionality.
column14: The controller is just as good as the old one, but if you were looking to use your phones Headphones with this controller think again. Microsoft decided that they would follow a different standard then the vast majority of headphones makers (iphone, mac, and most android phone). Any headphones using the CTIA standard will not work properly with this controller. The audio will come through, but due to using the OMTP standard instead of the more commonly used CTIA standard, you will need to buy an adaptor to use the mic and controls with this controller.  Oh, and did I mention I have yet to be able to find an adaptor that functions with this controller? Its not for sale on Microsoft site, nor at my local electronics store. So, if you're just looking to replace your broken controller this controller is more than fine, but if you are hoping to use the new head phone jack, make sure you have the correct kind of head phones before you buy.

column6: Final Fight 3
column13: A bit to easy for a Final Fight Game!
column14:
I had this for the SNES back in the day. It came out very late in the systems life span right before Nintendo stopped making games for SNES altogether. I always thought FF3 and Mega Man X3 were both rushed onto the market at the last minute. FF3 has some nice features. I loved the ability to choose your path through the game so you are not having to replay the same 7 stages over and over again. I liked the inclusion of the Super Meter bar and the dash moves as well. It helped speed the game along. FF2 was a very good game but it moved at a snails pace if you chose Haggar. FF3 isn't bad but the one thing that hurts it is the challenge factor. This game is way to easy. If you want any kind of challenge you have to set the bar to the highest meter every time you play and use a weak character like Lucia.

Story:
The story isn't much to speak of. Normal day at the office for mayor Haggar when a riot breaks out right in the middle of Metro City. So all 4 characters head out to clean up the streets. Maybe the Mayor is trying to save money and cutting down on the law enforcement payroll. After you see a huge hole in the wall at the beginning where you can tell someone broke out of a cell in the background I was expecting a much more grand final boss. It would have been better to have a intro/cut scene to explain who the main villain is? How did he become king of the Mad Gear gang? Was he a lieutenant who got promoted? He reminded me of "Rolento" from the first Final Fight Game. Not a lot of explanation or plot development. The ending is pretty much the same for all 4 characters so there is not a lot of replay value added to play through the game as a different character.

Play Control:
This is where the game shines. The characters all move effectively and with the expanded moves offered you really can do a lot with each character. The controls are very responsive and the characters feels smooth not stiff or sluggish.

Characters:
Guy and Haggar are fun to play and you can zip through the game pretty easily with either character. Lucia and Dean both pretty much suck. The villains are just so so. Some bosses you will recognize but most are one dimensional and require little strategy to defeat.

Difficulty:
There is none the game is a breeze. The first FF game for the SNES is extremely hard and it is hard to just make it halfway through the game. FF2 the difficulty was evened out and is a solid game all the way around. FF3 though is way to easy. Even novice players should finish this game quickly. This is one of the reasons the game seems unfinished. One thing that Double Dragon always had over the final fight series was the environmental hazards through the stages. It would have been nice to see some of those elements put into this game especially in the Steel mill.

Verdict:
I always compare the Final Fight Games to the old Double Dragon series. Very similar storylines and plots. The game has updated moves and features but the challenge is nowhere to be seen which really hurts the replay value. Its a nice game to play through once but definitely not worth owning. Very average game 3 stars.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Recon 30X Chat Communicator Gaming Headset - Xbox One (compatible w/ new Xbox One controller), PS4, PC, Mac, and Mobile
column13: Comfortable and affordable - can also be used on your phone and ps4
column14:
Overall a very functional and extremely comfortable chat head set designed for the newer Xbox One controllers (the updated version with a 3.5 mm jack that was released in June 2015). As long as you have this newer controller it is very easy to operate. Simply plug it into the 3.5 mm jack and you're good to go. There are 2 basic physical controls - a mute slider and a volume adjustment knob.

Incoming and outgoing audio quality is decent and perfectly fine for its intended purpose of voice comms. The best aspect of the headset is it's long duration comfort qualities. The slotted ear cups provide ventilation, sits very gently on your ears, does not press into the arm frame of your glasses and has an 'open' cup design allowing you to freely hear the game audio through your TV's audio setup. The boom mike utilizes a thin stick with full flex motion that is easily adjusted to keep out of your sight lines.

While the headset is clearly branded and designed to complement your X1 experience (eg - the green accent trim) the use of the 3.5mm jack provides flexibility to utilize the device with other systems such as the PS4 (all controllers have a 3.5mm jack) or even as a voice chat mike plugged into your phone. Terrific value, comfort and functionality.

column6: PDP AG7 True Wireless Headset for Xbox One
column13: Fits my large noggin comfortably; lots of bass, and a bass boost button for even more
column14:
Thank you PDP for sending this to us for review!

Performance Designed Products (PDP) has become well known for their brightly colored controllers and glowing neon headsets, as well as many other gaming related peripherals. We have purchased some of their lower priced controllers in the past, like their Rock Candy line. While the products always functioned as expected, they did feel less durable than their OEM counterparts. It seems like PDP is really stepping up on their build quality with recent products, and the Afterglow AG 7 headset is emblematic of this.

The AG 7 feels really solid. It is adjustable for large to small heads, and the top strap has quality padding that should last quite a while, with a firm grip holding it on your head without being uncomfortable, though it could get sweaty after a while. The ear pads are also removable, and the interior of the headphone is accessible, so modding is possible. However, putting those pads back on is not easy at all. The size adjustments click firmly into place, and don't slide around by accident. On the whole, it feels well built and strong, with solid plastic and metal holding it together. I expect them to last a fairly long time with regular use; as long as they are not bent unnaturally far in any one direction, since they do not fold DJ style. They have not given up on their trademark color schemes for the Afterglow model line ‚Äì this one glows a bright neon green while in use on Xbox One; for other uses, the glow is entirely optional, and just wastes batteries.

When plugged into a PC, the AG 7 identifies itself as an Xbox One controller. Since it does not identify as a sound device, Windows can't use it as one. Of course there are no controller buttons, so it can't be used that way either. There is a 3.5mm jack that can be used like every other headphone, but none of the extra features are available when used this way. My cellphone did register it as a headset, and the microphone sound was very clear for the other listener. I had much less success on PC, as I couldn't get the microphone to work acceptably there.

On Xbox One, the system instantly recognizes it as a headset and will quickly route sound and chat functionality to the headset. It was pretty much plug and play, and it worked very well. I don't play Xbox games online, so I wasn't really able to test that part, but if it sounds as good as it

So, after all of that, how does it sound? Well, it still follows the unfortunate modern pattern of boosting the bass above most other frequency ranges. The nice thing about PDP here is that they actually put their frequency response chart right on the box, which I greatly appreciate. They compare Pure Audio with Bass Boost, and show competing response charts with them both. Bass boost pushes up everything from about 200Hz on down by about 10db, which is quite a lot. The graphs also show a large spike at around 9-10KHz, which does noticeably improve the high end compared to other gaming headsets we reviewed recently, like the SteelSeries. Unfortunately, most of the midrange and lower treble is still substantially recessed, and it sounds that way. But at least they are honest about it, and for that, I applaud them.

If it's not obvious, I am not a fan of the massively boosted bass on modern gaming headsets. It's mostly because I know what good audio sounds like; I have invested much in my home audio system. But, by publishing the frequency response graphs, it is much easier to make intelligent equalizer decisions to make them sound much better for PC or mobile use. With some strategic cuts (and a few boosts, also) they sound pretty good after all. My biggest disappointment, outside of how they sound unequalized, was that I could not get the microphone to work well on either of my PCs. And that it's wireless only on Xbox One. But, there it works quite well. If I ever had a need to play Xbox One without my normal speaker system on, or play a game that my children should not hear, I won't hesitate to grab the PDP Afterglow AG 7.y Xbox One without my normal speaker system on, or play a game that my children should not hear, I won't hesitate to grab the PDP Afterglow AG 7.

column13: Not only do they provide a grippier feel with less slippage (then a new controller) but the extra height gives a little better l
column14:
I got these purely to FIX my ps4 analog sticks. The rubber had been coming off of them. What I did was rip all the remaining rubber off the sticks. I then put these on and they fixed the problem completely. Not only do they provide a grippier feel with less slippage (then a new controller) but the extra height gives a little better leverage for aiming in games.

I didnt see this addressed too much in the reviews here. Important to note one thing though. If you have uneven rubber on your analogs, from wear, you may need to rip the rest off for it to fit on properly. If the rubber is uneven before placing them on they wont fit right. I had this issue until I ripped all the remaining rubber off. This shouldnt be an issue if your controller is already worn out, since these are a permanent fix and WILL fit tightly without coming off, in my experience. They are very cheap and you get 4 of them, so its very easy to replace them but they seem like they will last a very long time.

Wasnt sure which brand to go with but after getting these I can confirm that they are a great fix for the ps4 controller

column6: Splatoon
column14:
Cant recommend this game enough! I've had such a blast playing this. What a refreshing take on a beat-to-death genre.

Things I like compared to other shooters:
1. No one "camps" because it does you no good in this game.
2. You spawn in the same spot every time. I find this a great idea because it makes it so much easier to learn the map.
3. The paint guns aren't like anything you've ever played with before. Which makes it so fun to tinker around with the different classes, sub weapons, and special moves.

I played this with a friend of mine that I play Destiny and COD with, and he was asking me how much a Wii U is after playing.

If you haven't bought a Wii U, this game might put that decision over the top. There's already a bunch of great titles, but this is just so different and fun that everyone who's ever enjoyed video games must experience.

NINTENDO: keep the DLC coming! The retro Nintendo Zapper was such a pleasant surprise for someone who grew up with that!

column6: Animal Crossing: New Leaf
column13: Funnest game ive played in a long time
column14:
I am 21 and brand new to the Animal Crossing series so this review is coming from an AC newbie to help other newbies. I am actually disappointed I haven't played this series long ago. This is hands down the funnest game I think ive played in a loooong time!
The graphics are absolutely adorable, cheerful and fun. Everytime you play, you cant help but to just feel happy and relaxed.
This game has absolutely no stress to it. Some activities you can do are catching bugs, fishing, collecting fossils, gardening, decorating and upgrading your house, fixing up your town up etc.
There are TONS of bugs and fish you can collect to fill up your encyclopedia and your towns museum. This can take weeks months or even years to complete since some fish and bugs are extremely rare. You can even collect badges for collecting a certain amount of items etc

I also love how all the cute animal villagers in your town each have their own distinct personality. You may find you like some of them, you may find you dislike some of them. But they are all extremely different with different dialog so it keeps the game fun and interesting!

And - This game takes place in real life time. When its night in real life, its night in the game, same with morning etc. You get rewarded the more you play. You will find yourself unlocking new shops and activities each day you play.

Overall WONDERFUL game. If you have a 3ds, you need this game.
I have been playing it ALL day, everyday, never getting bored, always wondering if i'm going to run into something rare. And always wondering what each new day is going to bring me.

column6: Black * Rock Shooter: The Game [Japan Import]
column13: Stella as in stellar, right? Name fits her well!
column14:
I brought this game off of Playstation Store, which has the game in English instead of Japanese (as other reviewers have said). So this review is about the game itself, NOT the product being sold here.

1. The Story
Great story! Humanity is on the verge of extinction by an alien race, and that's when BRS (or Stella) awakens and so begins Humanity's counterattack! However, the plot focuses around Stella herself, and has some great turns to it.

2. Gameplay
The battle system is more than just pressing buttons. The enemies have different attack patterns that you can figure out, remember, and react according to. You've got to use your head and not let your guard down, but the system is easy to use, and the different skills allow you to adapt and change your fighting style. Includes both offensive and support skills, along with passive skills that you can find by exploring the map.

There's also a number of challenges you can do to increase your stats, get new skills, or get new outfits or weapons! Along with unlocking pieces in the gallery.

3. Once you complete the game...

You get to aim for the real ending! After that, you get access to a lot of EXTRA missions and fighting the Class-A aliens all over again. I was honestly surprised by how much more there was to do after getting both of the endings.

4. Others
The voice acting is great for all the characters, and the graphics are nice and fit the game great. The music is great, Stage 4 especially fits the mood after what happens. Also, during some of the overhead dialogue you'll get to choose how you want to respond! The overhead ones don't affect the game (other than what is said in response), but in one of the PSS and NANA missions each, you'll get game-changer/movie scene-changer choices.

Overall, this has to be one of the best games I've ever played.

column6: Remember Me
column13: A great idea with mixed execution
column14: I've been playing and enjoying Life is Strange lately and decided to finish Dontnod's previous game, Remember Me. It's a great game on a technical level and environmental design, with a cool sci-fi soundtrack to boot. Everything else about the game has both highs and lows. When it comes to the fighting, there is a wide variety of actions available to the player. However, the Batman cloned fight mechanics could have been so much better. There is no true flow to combat. Sure, you can continue your combo once you leap frog but if that punch or kick isn't to that same enemy within the allowed amount of time, you're screwed. The platforming is really good but unfortunately that's all there is to this game. It's just platforming, platforming, fight, platforming, cut-scene, platforming, fight, platforming. It's like something is missing in-between because basing an entire game around climbing gets old fast. The memory remixes are awesome,so you can understand why Life is Strange uses the rewinding and fast-forwarding as a core mechanic. Unfortunately, it's so underutilized that it makes you want more similar remixing scenarios in the game. It's such a shame.  I don't want to be one of those people that goes "for a game called Remember Me, it sure isn't memorable! HAHA!" It's a good game with poor execution in major areas but it's also forgivable. I'm glad I got through the game and finished it. Life is Strange was probably the right way to go for Dontnod but it does make me hope they try a bigger project like Remember Me again.

column6: Dragon Age Inquisition
column13: There were so many great things about this game
column14:
There were so many great things about this game, really some spectacular things. There were also a lot of really awful things about the game (most noticeably, the ending) that were just awful, to the point that it took away from my ability to enjoy the great parts. I'm a huge fan of the series, and it just makes me sad to think of how much I did not enjoy this game. I had such high hopes for it.

SPOILER
SPOILER
SPOILER

SPOILER: For those that played the DA2 DLC, "Legacy"; remember how Corypheus just rolled out of that slumber and hit us with a fast paced, creative battle that, even if you got the rhythm of it, was a lot to handle at once? Don't expect that again. Apparently he sat around thinking about how not to fight a war, for all these years. The final battle was definitely a sheer button masher. The only tactics involved were, "Don't get hit by the periodic ranged attack" and "if you play a melee class, expect to run back and forth a lot". If you play a mage or archer, it's even more disappointing.

Your actions in the game have very little effect on the ending of the game, and there is no real risk of losing anyone. Even in DA2, you ran the risk of having to kill one of your companions, if your politics were in too much conflict. This, you're fine. There's one way to fight. There's one ending. It's done. There are different ways it can end in the slideshow epilogue; but they are focused more on leaving options open for the next game, so you shouldn't expect anything about your companions, the Inquisition as a whole, or most of what you did.

The politically correct overhaul of the Qunari was the worst part for me. The Qunari were my second favorite part of the series (after the Grey Wardens), and it really got on my nerves to see them retreated in such a way. It resulted in me really hating The Iron Bull, which was another big disappointment for me. If they wanted toinclude the mercenaries, Krem would have been a much better and more interesting companion.

Stories like Blackwall's really helped pull it out for me. It was just so full of fantastic and horrible, with a sea of button mashing turn-in quests in between. I wish I could hate it or love it, but instead I'm just very disappointed in it. I love to play the same game over and over. I've played it twice so far, and I'll play it more (at least once for each romance); but it will become a back of the shelf title for me. After I get through the last of the romances, I probably won't play it again.

column13: TRON Collector's Edition controller PL-3686. The Good, The Bad, & The Ugly.
column14: First, I don't know weather to give it one, or two stars...I'm on the fence...so, I'll give it two. I give it two, because I am a HUGE TRON FAN. I have seen the original, I know over 300 times, probably close to 400...if not more. I love the glow of the controller. It definitely has a very tron feel and look to it.  The Good. Unlike other users, I have not had the same controller malfunction issues with mine and I have about a hundred +/- hours on it.  The Bad. Although I have not had the same controller malfunction, as others, the controller [does] have some unintended movement artifacts in it. E.g. If I'm standing still, it will move slightly...sometimes. This is not an all the time thing.  The Ugly. I have had a malfunction in my controller, unlike the other users posting here. My malfunction comes in the part that is at the end of the cord....the breakaway cable, about 6 inches in length, including the USB plug. That barrel plug can be disconnected, to replace the breakaway cable. On my controller, that breakaway cable has an "open" in it, about in the middle. I contacted PDP, the makers of the controller, about the issue. They said they no longer make the controller; however, they would be able to send a replacement breakaway cable to me at no charge.

column6: Battlefield Hardline
column13: The Battlefield series seems to be getting progressively worse with each new release
column14: The Battlefield series seems to be getting progressively worse with each new release.  I liked Battlefield 2 and 4.  Didn't buy 3.  The way I determine whether a game is a lot of fun is whether I can continue playing it without getting tired of it.  I was excited when I bought this game, but after trying it for a week or so, my assessment is that it simply is not as engaging and enjoyable as the previous releases.  The whole police/criminal is just kind of lame.  The weapons offerings, and the ability to earn more weapons/equipment are not that great.  You have a rank-promotion system like in the previous games, but, at least as far as I can tell having gotten to rank 10, you don't earn anything that makes playing the game more fun.  My advice would be to pass on it and wait to see what they come out with next.  I am going to trade it in and re-purchase the Battlefield 4 game.

column6: Puppeteer
column13: which sony puts out the best games on its system
column14:
Arrived in the shape advertised. The game is incredible though. I did see a gamespot review of a 9 a long time ago, but often assume certain games get overrated so I didnt pick it up right away. It is actually a first party sony game, which sony puts out the best games on its system.
This game is easily on the level of the best games on the system, without a doubt. The presentation (sound and visuals, art style) is one of the best Ive seen, especially for a mostly side scroller type of game. Boss fights are some of the most entertaining Ive played in any game , despite genre. They are fleshed out like something youd see in a god of war game, not a side scroller. Way above and beyond what youd see in any mario game as far as bosses. The traversal is very creative too and the game constantly switches up the environments and style of gameplay to keep the pacing constantly fresh. Mastering that type of pacing is something very few games achieve. The game is nonstop and never drags.

Cant say enough good things about the game. Its worth much more then its price.

My 11 year old got three new controllers for his birthday,
this one,
the USPRO [url]http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00OZBQJDC?redirect=true&ref_=cm_cr_ryp_prd_ttl_sol_22[/url]

all three took and held their charges about the same,

In the end it came down to button feel/action,
Sony was the best (but not by much, especially at 3 times the price),
this eXuby was a close second
and the USPRO was a close third,
a great remote so far, with a slightly cheaper feel.

But honestly it's so close either one is great for the money.
