column6: Castlevania: Order of Ecclesia
column13: A fine 2D game in the Castlevania series
column14:
It's a fine addition to the 2D Castlevania series. The gameplay and story are engaging, and the weapon-glyph system is fun to use.

The Metroidvania elements are a little less pronounced here, as there are generally fewer movement-based obstacles to exploration than what one might expect in "Symphony of the Night."

I enjoyed many of the Action-RPG elements, especially the weapons system that differs in stats, speed of use, and geometry (space on the screen that is counted as a hit).

My primary complaints?
-The difficulty curve is a bit uneven. I found some sections to be trivial, while others brutal, and it wasn't terribly consistent.
-Some important items are far too difficult to gather, either because of absurdly low drop rates or overly picky platforming mechanics.

column14: I was chosen to receive this product at a promotional price in commitment to post an honest product review. With that being said, this is an awesome game for kids!! column6: IPEGA II Generic Bluetooth Controller Android Wireless Game Controller Gamepad Joystick for iPhone/iPod/iPad/Android Phone/Tablet PC Black
column13: the material used on the main body is almost like a rubberized plastic coating
column14: first off if you have a IOS device DO NOT get this controller(unless you are jail-broken, or running certain emulators). i had a very small amount of time using this controller on Android and I have a somewhat vague understanding of Android as well, but the controller does work with both OS! the material used on the main body is almost like a rubberized plastic coating,obviously this material is supposed to give you more of a grip and hold of the controller, but i'm afraid that it will slowly deteriorate over time from the acids in your hands. the clip that holds the phone in place feels and sounds(when extending the clip out) really cheap, the spring inside sounds very rough, and could give out after a good amount of usage, but it still does its job at the moment(this isn't a major problem for me because my phone is always hooked up to my TV). Other than that the controller is very solid, the button layout is basically the same as an Xbox controller, the buttons and D-pad don't feel cheap at all and have a glossy finish, but the start and select buttons are both rubber. but i feel like you do need to have more applied pressure with certain buttons, analog sticks feel really good and do click if pressed down in the center, the triggers were more like buttons, and were definitely in a weird place but it is very easy to get used to. the manual was poorly translated to english but it was still understandable, and does come with a Micro USB cable for charging, also the battery life is really great! long story short, if your looking for a small budget, but still good quality bluetooth controller, then this is the one for you

column6: God of War: Ascension
column13: Do you really care about consumers, game producer SONY?
column14:
First of all, I didn't buy from amazon, but I couldn't help to make comment here. As a customer, I am getting angry. Game producers are creating rediculous products, and seriously I don't think they ever care about customers's experience.

I got the game from PSN+ game download. The download is ~30G, I was super excited. After hours of downloading, finally I was able to start the game.

And then the game asked for downloading updates. 9 updates. OK fine.

The first update 630MB. OK, I was still excited, sat still and wait.

The second update still 630MB. ...

And the then the third one is still 630MB. And that was the time I completely lost my patience. I am the father of two kids, was video game fan for very long time, but for now I am really sorry but you are wasting my time.

Are you kidding me? Is it that hard to update your online digital download source?

No wonder the whole gaming industry is losing customers that fast.

column6: Turtle Beach - Ear Force Stealth 500X Premium Fully Wireless with Surround Sound Gaming Headset - Xbox One
column13: Great for the average joe, awful for audio enthusiasts
column14:
Right off the bat I want you to know - If you own a nice pair of headphones, Beats Solo2, V-moda's, Senns, etc. you will NOT like the sound quality of this headset. If you don't, and this is your first audio listening equipment beyond some apple earbuds or 30 dollar earbuds/headphones, these will be fine.
TL;DR at the bottom if you just want a quick list.

Construction is fine here, nothing felt wobbly or janky whatsoever. Solid stuff.

Comfort is a mixed feeling for me. It felt really cheap with the earpads and head padding, it squeaks when you move and doesn't really offer a seal. I know it's going for less heat over long sessions, and while I appreciate that, I like a sealed sound for gaming. These will not become hot or make you sore, even with my large and thick glasses frames. The cheap feeling really puts me off, but I have to give credit where it's due, they are comfy enough.

Sound.
Yikes.
So I installed and updated the thing, etc, so I know I was hearing it at it's best. It's not good.
There's no custom sound options, you just have 12 presets, 4 of those are not surround, leaving you with 8 options. 7 of these 8 options sound incredibly veiled (like listening with a pillow between your ears and the drivers), leaving me with one option I sorta found passable, Movie 2.
Movie 2 is super V shaped, like the actual letter itself. The trebles are so sharp simply reloading my gun in Halo and hearing the metal made me cringe. Bass is there, but not even boomy mind you, these thing's bass is not strong enough for a gaming headset IMO, gaming headsets should sound boomy and have loud thuds, it helps the immersion. This headset doesn't perform well enough with bass. It doesn't perform well with sound in any area to be honest, all the presets are awful.

One last note, they are completely wireless with Xbox. It's awesome. They have to be wired up to the computer if you want to chat with your friends, and it doesn't support surround on the PC with the included stuff. At least not proper surround. If you're not chatting with friends, you can run a double sided 3.5mm jack from your computer into the transmitter, and get wireless analog audio from your PC.

All in all, while they are comfy and made well enough, if you are more familiar with high end audio, DO NOT buy this headset. Incredibly veiled with awful presets and a lack of bass.
If you're an average joe looking to go completely wireless from your xbox, these will be a great deal if you can snag them for under 180 bucks.it doesn't support surround on the PC with the included stuff. At least not proper surround. If you're not chatting with friends, you can run a double sided 3.5mm jack from your computer into the transmitter, and get wireless analog audio from your PC.

All in all, while they are comfy and made well enough, if you are more familiar with high end audio, DO NOT buy this headset. Incredibly veiled with awful presets and a lack of bass.
If you're an average joe looking to go completely wireless from your xbox, these will be a great deal if you can snag them for under 180 bucks.

column6: TTX Wii U Pro Controller - Black
column14: I actually didn't originally see this on Amazon when I was looking for a Wii U pro controller and ended up going to a local game store. They had this exact controller there (luckily for the same price as Amazon) and I picked one up.  Unlike other controllers I've seen here that have bad reviews, this one actually acts as a PRO controller, not a classic controller. I've been able to use this with games that only support the pro controller. It also has a rechargeable battery that lasts a good amount of time (I haven't actually ran it totally out yet) as well as the typical vibration force feedback. All the buttons work well and it doesn't feel as though it's going to fall apart in a month.  If I had to find some cons, it's that the controller is a bit lighter weight than you'd expect and the joysticks are a bit more stiff than those on the Wii U Gamepad (but not uncomfortably stiff). That being said, I am very happy with this controller and will likely buy another one. It's pretty hard to beat at half the price of the Nintendo branded pro controller.  EDIT (1/13/16): As it turns out, the games I tested it on can be played with the classic controller as well as the pro controller (see second edit below). So I am not 100% positive it acts as a PRO controller, however, I have yet to have any issues with this controller at all and it has worked with every game I own (see comments below for list of games I've used it on). The battery still holds a nice charge and the joysticks are holding up. No complaints.  EDIT (1/18/16): I have used this controller with New Super Mario Bors U which, as I understand it, does not support the classic controller. Thus confirming that this controller DOES act as a PRO controller, and not a classic controller.

The controller I bought for use with my PC and the results I got were absolutely splendid, the controller felt ergonomically excellent, the buttons were in all the right places, response time was VERY fast and accurate. The bumpers did receive a pretty significant internal change that made the controller MUCH better, the bumpers are no longer as stiff as they were before, I feel comfortable just leaving my fingers in between the triggers and bumpers which allow me to push both at the same time with just my index fingers. All in all, if you're looking to use this on PC I cant recommend this controller enough... for most games, 2D games are fine using the controller's d-pad although I personally recommend using a dualshock controller for most comfortability, although if you's fine with the d-pad placement on the controller for 2D games then this controller is perfectly fine, I own a dualshock 4 myself so I'm covered for 2D and 3D games with both controllers but if you're looking for choosing between the dualshock 4 and this controller I can guarantee you that both perform practically identical, so the only thing standing between you and either controller are the $60 in your wallet and which button layout you prefer.

Happy gaming :).

column6: CTR: Crash Team Racing
column14:
Once again, gaming's beloved ex-Naughty Dog marsupial has been hopping around from one development team to another, and this time's lucky group of ducklings happens to be Radical Entertainment. They're history with video games is rather mixed, consisting of games such as the [[ASIN:B00004SVS1 \\\edutainment\\\\\" Mario]] [[ASIN:B00004SVS2 games on NES]], as well [[ASIN:B00004SVWM the abominable Wayne's World game on the same console]], but in later years, they've received positive reception from handling licenses such as [[ASIN:B0007OSLAA The Incredible Hulk]] and [[ASIN:B000095ZH5 The Simpsons]]. How did they do with their first Crash game? Let's find out.

While the [[ASIN:B000034DCF previous Crash]] [[ASIN:B00008NRM7 racing games]] had the same nonsensical story involving an alien that wants the characters to race for amusement, this game settles on a rather unappealing scientific genius trying to maintain a dangerous amusement park, but alas his Power Gems have been stolen. To get them back, Crash has to go and collect Power Crystals to activate jump pads to nab the missing Gems. Wait...I thought this was a racing game? Power Crystal collecting is involved in this?

Believe it or not, Crash Tag Team Racing indeed does have a lot more than just arcade-esc kart-racing. The single-player adventure will have you move around in elaborate worlds that are not unlike those of [[ASIN:B0001CJEJU Crash Twinsanity]], albeit more compressed and confined than such. At first, I was slightly disappointed in how the game doesn't run at 60fps like Twinsanity does, but I've grown accustomed to it quick. The sense of humor, on the other hand, is what I still find flawed. Funny moments are not as common as before, as there are only 11 minutes of cutscene footage for the plot, and even then they don't focus on humor as much as they should. Meanwhile, the game encourages you to kill Crash yourself by various over-the-tops means labeled as \\\\\"Die-O-Ramas\\\\\", a collection of forced gags whose punchlines get detected the moment the game indicates you can trigger something with a suspicious object, therefore losing its comedic factor instantly. Also, please don't press any buttons during the loading screens unless you LOVE hearing burps and farts.

Now with that out of the way, there is quite a lot to do in the amusement parks you visit. Scattered all around the place are Wumpa Coins and breakable boxes (as well as enemy penguins), allowing Crash to do his thing and collect bunches of coins by smashing stuff in sight. There are also gates that would take you to a track, and allow you to select a game mode for what kind of racing you want to do. There is the usual 3-lap racing, a 1-lap time trial, running into things, etc. There are even minigames you can play which can consist of stylized shooting galleries or penguin bowling. Power Crystals can be earned in several ways - You can win a race, place first in a different game mode or minigame, buy them off of NPCs, find them in the worlds themselves, or even go on fetch quests (which are usually for unlockable costumes and characters). The amount of variety there is to reaching your goal of gathering all these Crystals is actually pretty admirable, and the controls work nicely enough, if a tad loose. The bowling minigame is particularly my favorite (aside from racing of course) due to the constant change-up of lanes and further ability to control your ball.

Of course, racing is the key gameplay in a game with \\\\\"Racing\\\\\" in the title; there are a good amount of tracks to choose from, but they are honestly not so inspired in comparison to Crash's earlier kart-racing ventures or even [[ASIN:B000F1TI98 Pac-Man World Rally]]. They're just...there, to serve their purpose as tracks and not that much more. The item selection is kind of lackluster, too, but fortunately, I find myself clashing with my opponents too much to care! Kart-clashing is the selling feature to the racing mechanics in this game, and that said, using a gun turret with types of ammo depending on the kart you hijack is addictive; it's always fun to witness a kart blow up after doing enough damage to it, and I can even place first while on an opponent's kart!

Overall, while this definitely not a [[ASIN:B00009WAUD Mario Kart]] by any means, Crash Tag Team Racing does still manage to put together an interesting collage of gameplay concepts and ideas that mostly work out for the better in the end. Beneath the unnecessary bodily sounds and obnoxious voice for Crash (this is the first game where Crash gets to speak in gibberish thanks to Jess Harnell) is a game that is by no means perfect, but still shines enough for players to have a good time with it.id, using a gun turret with types of ammo depending on the kart you hijack is addictive; it's always fun to witness a kart blow up after doing enough damage to it, and I can even place first while on an opponent's kart! Overall, while this definitely not a [[ASIN:B00009WAUD Mario Kart]] by any means, Crash Tag Team Racing does still manage to put together an interesting collage of gameplay concepts and ideas that mostly work out for the better in the end. Beneath the unnecessary bodily sounds and obnoxious voice for Crash (this is the first game where Crash gets to speak in gibberish thanks to Jess Harnell) is a game that is by no means perfect, but still shines enough for players to have a good time with it."

column6: Playstation 2 Corded Controller
column13: A cheaply built third-party controller like anything else
column14:
First off, this Pelican Edge controller has been rebranded and is now sold at GameStop for literally 1/3 the price. It's absolutely identical. The only change is the logo on the front. One has a Pelican logo, the other says GameStop. They both even say "www.pdp.com" on the back, so it's the same manufacturer, same design, same quality, just the logo (and price) are different. Don't spend $30 on a PS2 controller.

Secondly, the controller isn't so great. It's a cheaply built third-party controller like anything else. Sadly, Amazon isn't selling it for cheap.

The controller body is slightly smaller than the original Sony PS2 Dual Shock. If your hands get cramped after playing for a while on the original controller, this one is even worse. The face buttons on the controller are inexplicably smaller as well, and they seem to be located closer to the analog sticks. Your thumb will accidentally move the right stick all the time when you're actually trying to push the X or Square buttons.

The face buttons are not very responsive. I've had more than a few cases when the game didn't react unless I pressed the button as hard as possible. I guess this is a symptom of the pressure-sensitive buttons that all PS2 controllers use, but some are better than others.

The L2 and R2 shoulder buttons are also REALLY flimsy and wiggle around inside the socket a ton. It looks like the buttons could fall right out, they rock back and forth at an angle so badly. You would have to see it to believe it.

Lastly, I bought this controller because it is advertised as having an "Enhanced D-Pad." I'd like to know what that is supposed to mean, because this d-pad is as bad as any controller I've used. The diagonals are not precise whatsoever. If you play any 2D games you will run or jump into things and die over and over. If you press up or down the controller often interprets it as a left or right diagonal. I think out of the big three console companies, only Nintendo got d-pads right.

This controller is not sturdy or precise, and this is true with both versions of the controller I own. Like I said, they are identical.

column14: This lets you connect Xbox 360 controllers to you computer for use in video games. Some games will have built in Xbox 360 support and others you will have to go into the options to configure your controllers. It works great and is easy to set up, just plug it in and let the drivers install then sync the controllers you want to use(up to four controllers at once). This receiver is a little light and seems like if stepped on it would break so you have to take care of it. The wireless range is pretty decent so you wont have to worry about being to far from it. column6: Regular Show: Mordecai and Rigby in 8-bit Land - Nintendo 3DS
column13: Other reviewers say that the graphics are crap, the audio is lofi and the mechanics are ...
column14:
Against popular opinion, I have to rate this title highly. It is everything an NES game used to be and this is all it should be seen as. Other reviewers say that the graphics are crap, the audio is lofi and the mechanics are broken but I found none of this to be true. The game is incredibly hard but keeps you coming back for more. The graphics and sounds are exactly what you would find in a vintage platformer and the multi-genre spanning works wonderfully. If you rate this against other 3Ds games, then yes, it is not the best. but if you consider it to be a new classic then it holds up against mario bros. 1, Megaman, Wonderboy and Alex Kid.

The game is so hard in fact that I tore my thumb nail, bloodied my elbow and lost my voice by the time I beat it but it was well worth it and I will be playing it again considering the New Game + mode. Asie fom the difficulty the game is actually quite forgiving. Continues and check points make this so. This game should not be overlooked for under ten bucks.

column14: I bought this game in 2005 without ever playing an Animal Crossing game before, and I loved it. I became a Turnip addict, constantly meeting up with people for big turnip sales, raking in those bells. It was fun designing the house, interacting with the NPCs, and doing all the activities with other people through WiFi. When this came out online handheld gaming was just starting to blow up, so it was pretty cool to be playing something like this at the time. I had four or five friends who had the NDS or NDS Lite, and we all played this game together. This is the kind of game you could pick up and play today and it would still be fun. I don't own a 3DS, but if I get one I'll be pulling this game out of my closet and playing it day one.

column6: Middle Earth: Shadow of Mordor
column14:
The best way to describe this game is it's a combination of the open-world gameplay of Assassin's Creed and the combat of the Batman Arkham series. It's truly a never-ending type of game because you can just play it to slaughter orcs, which is great if you've had a bad day. I had to take off one star for three reasons:

1) There's too much needless collecting. Completing the main storyline only gives you 50% of total game completion. In order to get 100%, you need to collect all the artifacts and Ithildin, as well as complete all the hunting and survival challenges, weapons missions, and other side missions. All of that is completely optional, and I didn't bother doing them all. Really, all that stuff is for trophy nuts who are addicted to getting trophies. I wish they made it mandatory to complete most of those side missions and/or get those collectibles in order to advance the main storyline, but you can easily complete the game without even doing one of the aforementioned tasks.

2) I should have bought the original, non-GOTY game. The DLC is pretty useless. Specifically, The Bright Lord campaign is WAY too difficult after the first two or three missions. I don't know why they upped the difficulty so much. Doesn't make sense to me, so I just filed my game into my CD case and called it a day. As far as I'm concerned, once I beat the main crux or storyline of a game, that's it for me. All DLC is just a cash cow for developers.

and,

3) The game gets repetitive after a while. Unless you enjoy slaughtering orcs if you've had a bad day or week, expect to not play this game again once you've already beaten it.

4 stars.

column6: Far Cry 4
column14:
Fun game. Graphics are superb and amazing on my 144hz LED monitor!
My you tube channel that shows the game play. Bear in mind I recorded at a lesser frame rate and resolution so it wouldn't take ages to upload.
https://www.youtube.com/channel/UC_nQjYOMkLlXAyRr1tRfdyQ/playlists

Pros:
1. Great graphics!!! I'm running an 8GB Card so it can take all settings max on 1080p.
2. Fun style of play. Easy learning and feel.
3. World is huge and I mean huge! They give you excellent modes of transportation. I barely use quick travel.
4. The story is a bit bizarre but once you get involved it's fun. I love stealth.
5. Customize game play. It lets you disable and enable a wide variety of options.

Cons:
1. Night time is way to short! I like to do my jobs at night and its not very realistically dark like Far Cry 2 and it only lasts for around 10-15 minutes.
2. No weather affects unless you call wind a weather affect! One of my favorite thing was storms in Far Cry 2. This game, not one!
3. No multiple save options in campaign mode. Sometimes I like to save a new slot so I can go back later. Nope not this time.
4. No option to make it virtually impossible to beat. I like games that ramp up the difficulty. This only has 3 options, easy medium and hard. Where's infamous! When I get hit I want to get hit not feel like something annoying is shooting at me.
5. Check out the screen shot. It has some graphic issues but not much.

All and all this game fun to play and has great game play but it's the little things that matter to me. I figured Ubisoft would at least put weather in the mix. The night affects being shortened really put me in a downer mode. Very disappointing with that. As being a long fan of the Far Cry series, I believe this was made mainly for graphics and not for the true Far Cry fans who enjoy the realism.

If your looking for a visually stunning game then buy it. If your into more realism type of game, I would say buy it too because than your giving them money to make the next Far Cry hopefully more realistic all around. Either way is a win win for me:)

***UPDATE*** 09-09-2015

So I completed the game and went back and played Far Cry 3. Wow this game is a major upgrade compared to Far Cry 3. I changed my rating to 5 stars because of this. It's a lot more smoother and lot better graphics. Also it seems more realistic and has better stealth options. The pros outweigh the cons in this title based off of previous games.he next Far Cry hopefully more realistic all around. Either way is a win win for me:) ***UPDATE*** 09-09-2015 So I completed the game and went back and played Far Cry 3. Wow this game is a major upgrade compared to Far Cry 3. column6: Xbox 360 4GB Console
column13: Works perfectly! (Now that my dad bought the games, controllers, and hook-up cords separately)
column14: Okay, I just want to say that I bought this just a little over a month ago. The first thing is that it works just fine. However, it does NOW. I have two major complaints about this console they sent me: The big one first - when I first ordered it, it said it would come with one controller and the cords to hook it up. But, when the UPS truck came to my house and dropped it off 3 days later, I opened the box and there was nothing inside but the console: no games, kinect, hard-drive, controllers, not even the power cord and HDMI cord! JUST the console! I ordered this a month ago, and my dad JUST bought all of the things to hook it up: two controllers, a power cord, an HDMI cord, and two games, Madden NFL 15 and Need For Speed: Shift. Now if it had come with those five things, this would be a four and a half-star review (I'd still be bummed about no hard-drive or kinect, but not too bummed because you can just buy those seperately, but this review is three-star because no seller should make their customers buy THAT much stuff seperately). My second complaint is that the version of this console I was gonna buy was for $72, but when I confirmed my purchase, it said i had spent $89! Now I only have $11 left on my $100 Amazon gift card my Grandma got me for Christmas,  and barely any of the other stuff I want to buy is under $13, so I have high hopes that she'll get me another one this upcoming Christmas. However, now that my dad has bought everything else, it works perfectly. My dad, despite being a big football fan, finds Madden NFL 15 very hard, and both him and my brother LOVE Need For Speed: Shift. One of the few things my brother's been doing the past few days is playing that game! Plus, for a best-selling high-tech video game console, $89 is actually a REALLY good deal compared to some  of the others on Amazon.  Overall, if you wan't an xbox 360, but have the money to buy all the other stuff it SHOULD come with seperately, get this!

column6: Rune Factory 4 - Nintendo 3DS
column13: \That sounds weird but very much like your kind of game\" - family"
column14:
The easiest description is what I told my brother:
"Harvest Moon plus dungeon crawling. So, you fight, level up, and craft gear, but you also farm and date everyone."
"That sounds weird but very much like your kind of game."
And he was right! Playing this game is all I do when I get home from work, so beware if you want to maintain any sense of productivity.

The game allows for casual play if you just wanna chill, meet the characters, dress in silly costume combos, and meander through the dungeons. But you can also go full out, gear up, customize, tame the best monsters, and wipe everything. Overall I think there's something for everyone.

You like art?
- There are small cut scenes for important moments, like main character reveals, in a crisp, anime style. They're replayable from a spot in the basement of your house, in case you (god forbid) weren't paying attention the first time.
- You can also see certain outfits and headgear on your character as you run around the game world. Have fun pairing pumpkin heads with sheep costumes! The core appearance of your main character is set though.
- Give villagers headgear to see them potentially wear it while walking around the game world.

Are the characters interesting?
- Get to know them through random events (just like real life!) that expand upon personalities and histories of NPCs, and unlock story elements.
- Get super close to the eligible bachelors/bachelorettes and date all at once without penalty, unlocking more personal dialogue, and enabling you to make an educated choice in who to marry.
- Play as a male or female, or both! There are a couple save slots available.
- Each character has a unique voice that speaks relevant sounds or full sentences depending on the discussed topic. This is in English.

I want to fight!
- Each weapon category (I think there are 7 weapon types?) has tons of options within, and enhancing them with items allows for amazing optimization.
- Craft mass amounts of armor, accessories, and more to uniquely fit your play style.
- Bring two NPCs at a time to dungeons for extra help, and enlist the aid of monsters by taming them (and keeping them on your farm for free recipe ingredients).

I prefer Harvest Moon elements...
- Craft increasingly helpful farm tools to get more done in less time.
- Tame and care for monsters of your choice, some of which produce helpful ingredients to use in crafting.
- Expand your farm size or locate other patches of farmable land around the map for extra room.
- Spend "Prince/Princess" points to develop the town, add shops, and attract more tourists.

column13: Graphics show a ton of clipping and poor collision detection
column14: Other than a couple cameo appearances, this game has virtually nothing to do with the Game of Thrones show it's supposed to be based on. The combat mechanics are clunky (basically a copy of Dragon Age) and do little to differentiate the various skills/powers available. Graphics show a ton of clipping and poor collision detection. If your idea of combat is essentially pausing the game every few seconds, you might like it. But overall I found it underwhelming. Companion powers are at best tacked on, such as Mors' dog, and add very little to the game. Many of the dialog choices are false choices and actually do nothing to change the way the game progresses. In all, a rather poor game adaptation of a wildly popular show.

column6: Dying Light
column13: With the reviews I was expecting it to be much worse than it was
column14: This game really surprised me. With the reviews I was expecting it to be much worse than it was.  When I had seen previews it looked very impressive.  I held off because of the reviews. This game ended up being one of my favorite open world games.  Just be aware that it doesnt start off great.  You start off extremely weak and fighting enemies felt s***ty to me at first.  Your weapons break fast and hardly hurt the guys.  However you dont lose progress when you die. You just respawn at a farther location. When you come back, whoever you killed or injured remains that way. So eventually I grinded out all the enemies through many deaths. That part was not fun to me.  However, several hours into the game you do get alot stronger, with upgrades and better weapons and then the game becomes awesome.    The two main cities you explore in the game are extremely detailed and well done. The mobility and movement is some of the best ive seen. You can climb and jump rooftops easily once you get into the rhythym. That was another thing that took a few hours to get into a flow with.    The survival vibe and atmposphere was a great and unique experience.  I highly reccomend picking this game up and giving it some time. Definately dont judge by the first few hours. Spend some time with it, grind out the beginning and then it may really grow on you as it did for me.

column6: Homefront
column13: Very difficult, recommended mainly for single player campaign.
column14: This is more difficult than your average FPS. However, for me personally and other FPS die-hards out there, we do enjoy a challenging FPS every now and then. Some are just no challenge even on hardest difficulty, so this is nice and refreshing. The graphics are great, story is fiction and I enjoyed it. column6: Thrustmaster VG Thrustmaster SCORE-A Wireless Gamepad
column14: i was looking forward to this because the d-pad is a solid piece, unlike many other pads where its 4 protruding buttons that do not allow for the same smooth movement of "rolling" through directions. another selling point was that it would seemingly cover my android devices, and my windows computer for steam gaming. thrustmaster as a brand also inspired confidence.  android gaming it does alright. steam gaming it does not do at all. the buttons work in the launcher but not in any of the dozen games i tried. ergonomics of the device are pretty terrible. dont be fooled by the blown up image of the product. i wish there was a quarter for size before i purchased. its even smaller than the PS controllers. i have average size hands and this looks like it was made for a small toddler. buttons and  sticks are crammed. fingers don't quite sit right over the controls. this is made worse by the angle of the "horns". trying to position your hands to be within comfortable reach of all controls, results either unnecessary strain on your wrists, or arms and elbows having to be uncomfortably close. i've used about a dozen different game pads over the last decade of gaming. brands vary slightly in ergonomics that is really mostly just a matter of variation and you just get used to. but this is plain bad.  final flaw is the puzzling design choice was using triple A batteries which generally contain a lesser electrical charge. (yes i know you can find higher capacity aaa batteries but the bottom line is smaller storage space is smaller charge capacity, you could argue that you can find even large capacity AA batteries). whats puzzling about this choice is that usually smaller batteries are selected to save space, but the battery compartment here actually *wastes* internal space by leaving an empty gap that *almost* enough for a 4th aaa battery, but it does not use it. seems they should have made internals slightly larger to accommodate an additional aaa battery, or used the same space to accommodate 3 aa. this part of the review did not affect the score. it was just an observation on a strange design choice. the score is based on terrible ergonomics and lacking function in pc gaming.

column6: FC3Plus Multi Video Games System (Nes+Snes+Genesis+G Factor)
column14:
The controller ports are the same design as the Sega Genesis controller plugs, but are just a bit smaller than the Sega genesis Controllers, so the only controllers that are compatible are the ones that come with this system.

Normally that would be okay, however, since the cords are too short, you either need a really tiny TV, or be extremely near sighted too enjoy playing games with this. I have checked everywhere available, and there are no extension cables for these controllers. So, you are stuck with what you get here.

Also, a major gaff in design, is the power & reset buttons.

They are set in the opposite positions of where they should be --- literally, pressing the power button down, it depresses the way the reset button should, and the system shuts off. The reset button clicks when pressed, and stays in place --- I actually had to place a penny on the power button and tape it down in order to play a game, which only held for a short while before coming undone and the power shutting off.

My suggestion is stay away from this thing and go with another system that has a similar function --- there are others out there that play multi latform cartridge based games --- this one is not a good option.

column6: Thrustmaster T-Flight Hotas X Flight Stick
column13: You get what you pay for, I guess...
column14:
~ PROS ~
- One of the cheapest HOTAS sticks you'll find.
- Nice shape / comfortable grips.
- Throttle stick has a nice "catch" zone at 0 value, letting you easily kill your speed without switching into reverse.

~ CONS ~
- Cheap and noisy plastic construction.
- Catchy, inaccurate movement on every axis of the joystick.
- Huge deadzones that the configuration software won't fix.
- Short cord between the sticks makes fitting a keyboard between pretty difficult.

I've had my eye on a HOTAS setup for a while, and this one in particular for its affordability. I'm a huge fan of space flight games like Elite:Dangerous, Jumpgate, Vendetta Online, Starport Gemini and so on, but I didn't want to dish out hundreds for the immersion a simple throttle + joystick combo can offer. Long story short: I should have.

For a budget HOTAS this one of very few options on the market, which is a huge shame. The throttle stick isn't terrible and would work fine on its own (if you don't mind a little inaccuracy around the "catch" zone when trying to fine tune your thrust for landings), but the joystick is simply awful, with massive deadzones on every axis and very inconsistent, cheap-feeling tension throughout the movement ranges. For a game like Elite: Dangerous, precise yaw control is crucial for micro-adjusting your aim when you've got an enemy in the crosshairs, and the awkward tension of this joystick's yaw axis combined with its large deadzone will leave you swinging dramatically to the left and right of your target. Beyond the poor movement and feel of the stick, the cheap plastic makes a groaning/squeaking sound that I wasn't able to ignore, though I imagine this might have gradually improved if I had taken the time to break in the stick and wear down whatever component was causing the sound.

If none of the above deters you, then congrats! Performance aside, the entire unit feels comfortable to hold and the button placement feels fine, if perhaps a bit sparse. I was able to compensate for the lack of buttons by programming multiple button presses simultaneously, effectively grouping commands by treating the buttons on the throttle stick like "shift," "alt," "control" and so on. I found that the cable between the two sticks was long enough to let me rest each stick comfortably at shoulder width, but not long enough to allow my keyboard to fit between them, which made my overall setup pretty awkward and cumbersome. I tried playing with both halves of the unit connected, but I felt cramped and contorted, so I wouldn't recommend it.

If you simply MUST play with a HOTAS, but you're shopping on a budget and you don't mind trying to aim and steer as though you're riddled with Parkinson's, then go ahead and throw money at this stick. Otherwise, keep shopping around. I returned this product and eventually settled on a dual-joystick setup for about the same price that I much prefer.to hold and the button placement feels fine, if perhaps a bit sparse. I was able to compensate for the lack of buttons by programming multiple button presses simultaneously, effectively grouping commands by treating the buttons on the throttle stick like "shift," "alt," "control" and so on. I found that the cable between the two sticks was long enough to let me rest each stick comfortably at shoulder width, but not long enough to allow my keyboard to fit between them, which made my overall setup pretty awkward and cumbersome. I tried playing with both halves of the unit connected, but I felt cramped and contorted, so I wouldn't recommend it.

If you simply MUST play with a HOTAS, but you're shopping on a budget and you don't mind trying to aim and steer as though you're riddled with Parkinson's, then go ahead and throw money at this stick. Otherwise, keep shopping around. I returned this product and eventually settled on a dual-joystick setup for about the same price that I much prefer.

column6: NES Remix Pack
column13: Great collection of challenges from the old games
column14:
Great collection of challenges from the old games. Keyword CHALLENGES. These are not the actual full games. Not even close. There is a reverse version of super mario bros with luigi but thats the most complete game in the package. Everything else is challenges based on classic games.

I got this knowing that. I have all the old games preserved on emulation on a pc. So I wasnt looking for a compilation disc. This disc includes Two compilation games. NES Remix 1 and NES Remix 2. Both were released as downloads on the nintendo store. Each game has a main campaign type of path that is beatable with brief ending scenes. Once those are completed you have a third set of bonus levels. These are just more of the same types of levels but sometimes include challenges from different games. Aside from the main campaign paths you have many games that each have thier own sets of challenges. You get ratings in each challenge from 1 to 3 stars. The stars you unlock are what you use to unlock more stages in the main campaign. Its very forgiving and you dont have to beat everything to unlock all the main levels.

Game is very addictive though. Some challenges can be a little tricky at first. For someone who has played through so many games in the last nearly 3 decades, it was too easy overall. That was my only issue. Thats not so much a flaw as a personal perspective though. Everyone is different. There was some challenge though in some parts but most of it I went through very quickly. There is still alot of content though and it offers hours of gameplay with that nostalgic vibe. Presentation is great too.

column6: Mortal Kombat X
column14:
Mortal Kombat X is an awesome fighting game. It is fast paced, simple, and has tons of cool and VERY attractive male and female characters. The Fatalities are extremely kickass and gruesome, and the game looks absolutely amazing.

I love the Klassic Tower, and I watched a relative of mine play the full story. The game has a super good story that ends happily. I love everything about this game. If you wanna play a great fighting game, then I highly recommend that you play Mortal Kombat X.

column6: Sony PlayStation 4 PS4 Dualshock 4 Wireless Control
column13: Don't have PS4, bought it to use the bluetooth capability with MacBook
column14:
I actually don't have a PS4, I bought the controller so I could use it's bluetooth to play supported games on my macbook. So for me the only thing that could've brought this down from 5 stars is bluetooth lag, of which there is absolutely none. Totally seamless, virtually no setup was needed just set it in pairing mode like any other bluetooth device.

Since I don't have the console or a dedicated charger, had to find alternative means to charge it, and I found I can't use a wall charger, I have to charge it from my laptop USB port (which I googled and found other people saying the same thing).

If you're looking for a controller with bluetooth to game on your laptop, this is a great one.
